抽象的

Abstract

The pairing of massive data sets with processes—or algorithms—written in computer code to sort through, organize, extract, or mine them has made inroads in almost every major social institution. This article proposes a reading of the scholarly literature concerned with the social implications of this transformation. First, we discuss the rise of a new occupational class, which we call the coding elite. This group has consolidated power through their technical control over the digital means of production and by extracting labor from a newly marginalized or unpaid workforce, the cybertariat. Second, we show that the implementation of techniques of mathematical optimization across domains as varied as education, medicine, credit and finance, and criminal justice has intensified the dominance of actuarial logics of decision-making, potentially transforming pathways to social reproduction and mobility but also generating a pushback by those so governed. Third, we explore how the same pervasive algorithmic intermediation in digital communication is transforming the way people interact, associate, and think. We conclude by cautioning against the wildest promises of artificial intelligence but acknowledging the increasingly tight coupling between algorithmic processes, social structures, and subjectivities.

将海量数据集与用计算机代码编写的流程（或算法）相结合，对数据集进行分类、组织、提取或挖掘，这种做法已渗透到几乎所有主要的社会机构。本文旨在解读关注这一转变的社会影响的学术文献。首先，我们探讨一个新职业阶层的崛起，我们称之为“编码精英”。该群体通过对数字生产资料的技术控制，以及从新近被边缘化或无偿劳动者——网络帝国——中榨取劳动，巩固了权力。其次，我们表明，数学优化技术在教育、医学、信贷和金融以及刑事司法等诸多领域的应用，强化了精算决策逻辑的主导地位，这有可能改变社会再生产和流动的途径，但也引发了受其支配者的抵制。第三，我们探讨数字通信中同样普遍存在的算法中介如何改变人们的互动、交往和思考方式。最后，我们对人工智能的最疯狂的承诺提出警告，但承认算法过程、社会结构和主观性之间的联系日益紧密。

在我们这个科技痴迷的时代，算法扮演着一种特别神秘的角色，甚至披上了神性的外衣。“算法”之类的概念已经沦为草率的缩写，沦为俚语，用来形容将多部分复杂系统误认为简单、单一系统的行为。

—伊恩·博格斯特（2015）

The algorithm has taken on a particularly mythical role in our technology-obsessed era, one that has allowed it wear the garb of divinity. Concepts like “algorithm” have become sloppy shorthands, slang terms for the act of mistaking multipart complex systems for simple, singular ones.

—Ian Bogost (2015)

 
黑客道德与硅谷精神

20 世纪 40 年代，位于圣何塞和旧金山之间的圣克拉拉谷连绵起伏的丘陵以其梅子园和开阔的牧场而闻名。尽管斯坦福大学是电子领域的早期先驱，但它——“19 世纪强盗贵族和他的妻子的感伤愚蠢之作”——仍然被称为“农场”（O'Mara 2019，第 29 页）。它从田园象牙塔到全球经济强国的彻底转变源于冷战初期政府的大规模投资运动。凭借着将科学称为“无尽的边疆”（Bush 1945）的崇高语言，来自国防部的硬通货开始涌入大学，最终到达了西海岸。

In the 1940s, the rolling hills of the Santa Clara Valley, between San Jose and San Francisco, were best known for their prune orchards and open grazing fields. In spite of being an early pioneer in electronics, Stanford University—“the sentimental folly of a nineteenth century robber baron and his wife”—was still called “the farm” (O'Mara 2019, p. 29). Its radical transformation from pastoral ivory tower to global economic powerhouse originates in a campaign of vast government investment at the beginning of the Cold War. Riding the lofty language of science as “the endless frontier” (Bush 1945), hard cash from the Department of Defense started pouring into universities, eventually reaching the West Coast.

然而，与政府的联姻并不容易。越南战争和 20 世纪 60 年代反主流文化的兴起，使军事赞助（以及技术创新的军事化）越来越受到该地区新兴工程师和计算机科学家阶层的反感。为了宣布他们的自治，他们声称相信信息的自由流通、社区的政治优越性以及赠送和互惠的精神（Barbrook 1998、Fourcade & Kluttz 2020、Rheingold 1993、Turner 2006）。随着一次又一次的技术革命（半导体、个人电脑、互联网、生物技术、社交媒体等）的到来，永恒的硅谷文化神话开始成形。在帕洛阿尔托，大公司诞生于车库和地下室。没有人戴领带。高管都是大学辍学生。公司等级制度是扁平的。工程师们通过诸如火人节（Chen 2009，Turner 2009）等精彩的文化形式来颂扬这些价值观，也颂扬他们自己。但他们不羁的道德观和相关的无政府自由主义政治也发挥了意识形态的作用，帮助抹去了联邦政府介入的历史，并助长了“该行业先驱的商业成功完全归功于他们自己”的迷思（Barbrook & Cameron 1996）。尽管人们大谈社区和互惠交流，但科技领袖和普通民众仍然坚信个人主义、竞争和适者生存。

The marriage with government, however, was not an easy one. The Vietnam War and the rise of the 1960s counterculture made military sponsorship (and the militarization of technological innovations) increasingly objectionable to the rising class of engineers and computer scientists that populated the area. Eager to proclaim their autonomy, they professed their belief in the free circulation of information, in the political superiority of community, and in an ethos of gift-giving and reciprocity (Barbrook 1998, Fourcade & Kluttz 2020, Rheingold 1993, Turner 2006). As one technological revolution after another rolled in (semiconductors, personal computers, the Internet, biotechnology, social media, etc.), the myth of a timeless Silicon Valley culture began to crystallize. In Palo Alto, major firms were born in garages and basements. No one wore a tie. Executives were college dropouts. Corporate hierarchies were flat. The engineers celebrated these values—and themselves—through spectacular cultural forms, such as Burning Man (Chen 2009, Turner 2009). But their irreverent ethics and associated anarcho-libertarian politics fulfilled an ideological function, too, helping erase the history of federal government involvement and propelling the myth that the business successes of the sector's pioneers were entirely their own (Barbrook & Cameron 1996). Despite talk about community and reciprocal exchange, tech leaders and the rank and file alike maintained fervent beliefs in individualism, competition, and survival of the fittest.

2000年3月互联网泡沫的破灭引发了一场关键的转折。硅谷正处于十字路口。与互联网相关的公司——当时互联网还是一个相对较新的发明——难以实现长期盈利。谷歌等在经济危机中幸存下来的初创公司仍在免费提供服务，缺乏明确的盈利策略。随着Zuboff（2019）偶然发现所谓的“行为盈余”——人们在网络上漫游和活动时留下的数字痕迹——这种情况发生了改变。突然之间，搜索、聊天、社交互动等原本不盈利的业务线可以被重新利用，供广告商利用——事实也的确如此。公司开始将他们产生的偶然数据与机器学习的新算法技术相结合，以预测人类行为。广告支持的平台通常是开放的，名义上是免费的，开始取代昂贵的盒装软件的旧模式。现在，似乎任何人都可以开发应用程序，并且任何人都能负担得起使用费用。独立开发者可以获得巨额利润，而且有些开发者确实这么做了。

The bursting of the dot-com bubble in March 2000 initiated a critical transition. Silicon Valley was at a crossroads. Firms associated with the Internet—then a relatively new invention—struggled to demonstrate long-term profitability. Start-ups that managed to survive the economic bust, such as Google, were still offering their services for free, with no obvious strategy of monetization. This changed with the incidental discovery of what Zuboff (2019) calls the “behavioral surplus”—logged digital traces that people leave behind as they wander around and inhabit the web. Suddenly, unprofitable lines of business in search, chat, social interaction, and the like could be repurposed toward exploitation by advertisers—and they were. Companies started pairing the incidental data exhaust they were generating with new algorithmic techniques of machine learning to predict human behavior. Ad-supported platforms, often open and nominally free, began to displace the old model of expensive boxed software. Now anyone, it seemed, could make an app, and anyone could afford to use it. Independent developers could reap huge profits, and some did.

这种访问和开发民主化的另一面是用户监控和操纵的加剧。对用户隐私或消费者福利的谨慎如今阻碍了业务发展。创收日益依赖欺骗手段。为了吸引用户的注意力，开发者采用了赌博业首创的令人上瘾的技术（Hwang 2020、Schüll 2012、Vaidhyanathan 2018）。公司如今掩盖了自己对开放、自由和社会联系的崇高赞美，专注于从更多人那里获取更多数据，并巧妙地操纵这些数据以获得期望的结果：一次滚动；一次点击；或者更好的是，一次购买。这种“工具主义权力”（Zuboff 2019，第 8 页）的发展之所以成为可能，是因为现有法律被纳入信息资本主义的需求之中（Cohen 2019、Kapczynski 2020、Pasquale 2015、Pistor 2019）。首先，科技公司将通过 cookie 和追踪器产生的个人数据定义为丰富且可免费获取的数据。他们通过平台协议和看似无害的样板合同来获取这些数据，并将这一过程描述为互惠互利的交易。1其次，他们通过涉及专利和商业秘密的合法所有权履行来小心翼翼地保护他们的数据财富。一旦被标记上所有“法律特权标记”（Cohen 2019，第 64 页），这些本应位于个人或公共领域的数据就被有效地挪用并重新编码为私人资本或资产（Birch & Muniesa 2020，Pistor 2019，Sadowski 2020），就像现代的圈地或殖民过程一样（Couldry & Mejias 2019）。

The flip side of this democratization of access and development was the intensification of user surveillance and manipulation. Caginess about user privacy or consumer welfare now stood in the way of the business. Generating revenue increasingly turned on trickery. To capture the attention of users, developers employed addictive techniques pioneered in the gambling industry (Hwang 2020, Schüll 2012, Vaidhyanathan 2018). Belying their own exalted celebration of openness, freedom, and social connection, firms were now focused on generating ever more data from more people and artfully manipulating them to secure desired outcomes: a scroll; a click; or better, a purchase. What made the development of this “instrumentarian power” (Zuboff 2019, p. 8) possible was the cooptation of existing law to serve the needs of informational capitalism (Cohen 2019, Kapczynski 2020, Pasquale 2015, Pistor 2019). First, tech firms defined the personal data that were produced through cookies and trackers as abundant and free for the taking. They harvested them through platform protocols and seemingly benign boilerplate contracts that framed the process as a mutually beneficial exchange. 1 Second, they jealously protected their data bounty through legal performances of ownership involving patents and arguments about trade secrecy. Once marked with all the “indicia of legal privilege” (Cohen 2019, p. 64), the data that supposedly lay within individuals or in the public commons were effectively appropriated and recoded as private capital or assets (Birch & Muniesa 2020, Pistor 2019, Sadowski 2020), as if in a modern process of enclosure or colonization (Couldry & Mejias 2019).

在这些前所未有的对数字生产资料的所有权主张之下，一种新的阶级关系体系可能应运而生。本文分析了科技产业崛起以及通过算法2（以代码形式编写并在计算机上运行的指令集）重组社会进程所带来的社会分化。在下一节“编码精英的崛起与其他人走向自动化之前”中，我们认为数字资本主义的核心分歧在于我们所说的编码精英（他们掌握并控制着数据和软件）与网络帝国（他们必须生产、改进和处理用于输入或训练算法的数据，有时甚至到了自动化自身工作、让自己变得冗余的地步）。我们还表明，对技术和经济效率以及公平性的诉求是编码精英社会权力的重要组成部分。接下来，在题为“精算主义及其不满”的部分，我们将讨论算法方法在一系列职业领域（包括零售、交通运输、保险、社会工作、医学、银行、警察和司法系统）的传播所带来的更广泛影响。我们分析了算法工具在社会机构中推广的前景与陷阱，并思考其对社会阶级形成和不平等的影响。在题为“分类器及其不满”的部分，我们将展示算法过程也构建了人们如何相互认识和交往，以及技术中介如何与自我和社群的感知和生产相交叉。最后，我们将思考对这一技术轨迹未来可能路径的预测，并提出两个可能的方向。一个方向将回归到一个具身化但如今已被算法增强的赛博格自我。另一个方向将通向一个平行的非实体社会，在这个社会中，我们的数据自我与机构监护人互动，其后果是模糊且间接的。

Out of these unprecedented ownership claims over the means of digital production, a new system of class relations could now arise. This article analyzes the social divisions associated with the ascendancy of the tech industry and the reorganization of social processes through algorithms 2 —sets of instructions written as code and run on computers. In the next section, The Rise of the Coding Elite and the Pre-Automation of Everyone Else, we argue that the core divide in digital capitalism opposes what we call the coding elite, who hold and control the data and software, and the cybertariat, who must produce, refine, and work the data that feed or train the algorithms, sometimes to the point of automating their own jobs and making themselves redundant. We also show that claims of technical and economic efficiency, as well as fairness, are an important component of the coding elite's societal power. Next, in the section titled Actuarialism and Its Discontents, we discuss the broader effects of the diffusion of algorithmic methods across a range of occupational jurisdictions, including retail, transportation, insurance, social work, medicine, banking, police, and the judicial system. We analyze the promise, but also the pitfalls, of the generalization of algorithmic tools across social institutions and consider its implications for social class-making and inequality. In the section titled Classifiers and Their Discontents, we show that algorithmic processes also structure how people come to know and associate with one another, and how technical mediations intersect with the perception and production of self and community. Finally, we ponder predictions about the likely future paths of this technological trajectory, positing two possible directions. One leads back to an embodied but now algorithmically augmented cyborg self. The other leads to a parallel disembodied society where our data selves interact with institutional minders, with consequences that are ambiguous and indirectly felt.

但我们不要操之过急，而是要回顾 21 世纪初“世界存储、交流和计算信息的技术能力”快速提升的意义（Hilbert & López 2011）。各类组织将“数据指令”制度化（Fourcade & Healy 2017）不仅对科技行业，而且对整个资本主义都产生了重大影响。商业杂志宣称数据是“新石油”。现在，每家小公司、每家公共或非营利性机构都可以参与其中，尝试开采自己的资源。任何会编程的人都可以为此目的建立网站、开发应用程序或编写软件。任何网页都可能充斥着追踪器——而分析是将这些数据货币化的途径。

But let us not get ahead of ourselves and return, instead, to the significance of the rapid acceleration of the “world's technological capacity to store, communicate, and compute information” in the early 2000s (Hilbert & López 2011). The institutionalization of a “data imperative” (Fourcade & Healy 2017) across organizations of all types was game-changing, not only for the tech industry but for capitalism in general. Business magazines proclaimed that data were “the new oil.” Now every small company and every public or nonprofit corporation could get into the action and try to mine their own. Anyone with the ability to code could set up a website, build an app, or write software with that purpose in mind. Any web page could be filled with trackers—and analytics was the way to monetize it all.

在互联网泡沫破灭之后，硅谷这只凤凰浴火重生。一种由大数据和分析技术驱动的新型生产模式正在蓬勃兴起。他们也即将驾驭独角兽的信念让满怀希望的计算机科学家和工程师们不断涌入湾区。收入的增加使房价飙升，一个又一个社区的工薪阶层生活消失了，却留下了数十个无家可归者的营地（Herring 2014，Walker 2018）。这个地方的政治仍然坚定地保持着加州风格：原则上是进步的，但在实践中“不在我家后院”（Dougherty 2020，Eliasoph 1998）。硅谷工程师们加入了专注于激进延长寿命和其他超人类主义追求的边缘运动；通过食用代餐来消除浪费时间的活动（Thompson 2020）；或者像镀金时代的先辈们一样，建立雄心勃勃的新慈善机构（Giridharadas 2018），越来越多的人忍饥挨饿，露宿圣何塞和旧金山的街头。2019年冠状病毒病（COVID-19）大流行非但没有加速不可避免的清算，反而可能进一步鼓舞了科技“解决方案主义者”（Morozov 2013）的主张，并造成了新的不平等，例如围绕数字教育的不平等。

After the dot-com boom and bust, the phoenix of Silicon Valley rose from its own ashes. A new mode of production, powered by big data and analytics, was surging. The belief that they, too, were about to ride a unicorn kept hopeful computer scientists and engineers flowing into the Bay Area. Rising incomes sent property values soaring, emptying one neighborhood after another of its working-class life but leaving behind scores of homeless encampments (Herring 2014, Walker 2018). The politics of the place remained firmly Californian: progressive in principle, but “not in my backyard” in practice (Dougherty 2020, Eliasoph 1998). While Silicon Valley engineers joined fringe movements preoccupied with radical life extension and other transhumanist pursuits; eliminated time-wasting activities by eating meal substitutes (Thompson 2020); or, like their Gilded Age predecessors, set up ambitious new philanthropies (Giridharadas 2018), more and more people went hungry and slept in the streets of San Jose and San Francisco. The coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic, far from precipitating the inevitable reckoning, may have instead further emboldened the claims of tech “solutionists” (Morozov 2013) and created new kinds of inequalities, around digital education for example.

城市极端贫富并存，是算法社会赖以建立的新经济最显著的特征。这种区分以经典（马克思主义）的方式，在最极端的情况下，将资本所有者（主要是风险投资家、公司创始人和技术员工，其中许多人也以股票形式获得报酬）与为他们辛勤劳作的人（服务人员、分包商和日工，他们承受着生活成本上涨的大部分冲击，却得不到任何好处）对立起来。截至2018年，圣马特奥县是加州最不平等的县，最富裕的1%人群的收入是最贫困的99%人群的49.1倍（Sommelier & Price 2018）。旧金山湾区是全美收入差距扩大最快的地区之一：1980 年至 2018 年间，第 90 百分位家庭的收入增长了 60%，而第 50 百分位（中位数）和第 10 百分位的家庭收入分别增长了 24% 和 20%（Bohn & Thorman 2020）。黑人和拉丁裔在较低收入水平和科技行业劳动力的较低层级中所占比例也过高。2016 年，大型科技公司 78% 的员工是白人或亚裔。只有 30% 是女性（Tomaskovic-Devey & Han 2018）。其他数字资本主义中心（如亚马逊和微软的所在地西雅图）也有类似的情况，经历了类似的演变。

The copresence of extreme urban wealth and poverty is the most visible feature of the new economy upon which the algorithmic society is built. In a classic (Marxist) manner, this distinction pits, at its most extreme, the owners of capital (primarily the venture capitalists, the company founders, and the tech employees, many of whom are also paid in stock) against those who toil for them (the service workers, subcontractors, and day laborers who bear the brunt—and none of the benefits—of rising costs of living). As of 2018, San Mateo County was the most unequal county in California, with the top 1% making 49.1 times more than the bottom 99% (Sommelier & Price 2018). The San Francisco Bay Area as a whole was home to one of the fastest growing income gaps in the country: Between 1980 and 2018, incomes for families in the 90th percentile increased by 60%, while incomes at the 50th percentile (median) and 10th percentile grew by 24% and 20%, respectively (Bohn & Thorman 2020). Black and Latinx people were also overrepresented at lower income levels and in lower rungs of the tech industry labor force. In 2016, 78% of employees at major tech firms were White or Asian. Only 30% were female (Tomaskovic-Devey & Han 2018). Other hubs of digital capitalism (like Seattle, home of Amazon and Microsoft) had similar profiles and experienced similar evolutions.

编码精英：规模化的力量

卡尔·马克思曾指出，生产关系及其所衍生的意识形态形成与技术发展密切相关。他在《哲学的贫困》一书中的一段著名论述中清晰地阐述了这一观点：

Karl Marx famously saw relations of production, and the ideological formations they give rise to, as intimately linked to the development of technology. He stated the point clearly in a famous passage of The Poverty of Philosophy:

社会关系与生产力紧密相连。人们在获得新的生产力时，改变了他们的生产方式；而随着生产方式的改变，随着谋生方式的改变，他们也改变了他们的全部社会关系。手磨坊造就了有封建领主的社会；蒸汽磨坊造就了有工业资本家的社会。那些根据物质生产力建立起社会关系的人们，也根据他们的社会关系创造出各种原理、思想和范畴。（马克思，1920，第119页，着重号为我所加）

Social relations are closely bound up with productive forces. In acquiring new productive forces men change their mode of production; and in changing their mode of production, in changing the way of earning their living, they change all their social relations. The hand-mill gives you society with the feudal lord; the steam-mill, society with the industrial capitalist. The same men who establish their social relations in conformity with the material productivity produce also principles, ideas, and categories in conformity with their social relations. (Marx 1920, p. 119, emphasis added)

如今，与之对应的技术是由数据和算法驱动的软件系统。它为我们带来了一个拥有软件资本家的社会。

Today's equivalent technology is the software system fueled by data and algorithmic ingenuity. It gives us the society with the software capitalist.

一个新的精英阶层占据了数字化社会的上层——我们自觉地向米尔斯 (2000)致敬，将这个阶层或原型阶层称为编码精英。编码精英是由软件开发人员、技术 CEO、投资者以及计算机科学和工程教授等组成的星云，他们经常在这些有影响力的角色之间毫不费力地流动。在全国各地的大学，尤其是在斯坦福大学，学术界和科技行业之间的隔阂通常很薄（O'Mara 2019）。教授们在自己的初创公司、大公司的关键职位、政府资助的研究实验室和教室之间流动。在这个世界上最有价值的是那些接触和理解计算机代码的人。最有权势的是那些拥有代码并可以雇用他人按照他们认为合适的方式部署代码的人。

A new elite occupies the upper echelons of the digitized society—a class or proto-class that, in a self-conscious nod to Mills (2000), we call the coding elite. The coding elite is a nebula of software developers, tech CEOs, investors, and computer science and engineering professors, among others, often circulating effortlessly between these influential roles. At universities around the country, and even more at Stanford University, the wall between the academy and the tech industry is often thin (O'Mara 2019). Professors circulate between their own start-ups, key positions in large firms, government-sponsored research labs, and classrooms. Most valued in this world are those people who touch and understand computer code. Most powerful are those who own the code and can employ others to deploy it as they see fit.

掌握计算技术会赋予人们特殊的力量。这些力量同时涉及文化、政治和经济。在文化方面，编码精英居住在值得信赖的数字世界中（Espeland & Stevens 1998、Golumbia 2009、Porter 1996）。由于他们的形式主义是数学上可证明的，这些技术显得具有普遍性，并且远离混乱的人类政治世界（Agre 1997、Forsythe & Hess 2001、Ribes et al. 2019 ）。编码精英将计算发展为几乎所有学科（ Hofman et al. 2017 ）突破的关键，包括社会学（Watts 2014）；改变政府行动的每个领域（Fourcade & Gordon 2020、O'Reilly 2010）；并且通常解决人类社会面临的大多数问题（Morozov 2013）。但只有内行人才能看透他们的神秘语言（Burrell 2016），通过它找到解决棘手问题的方法，并在此过程中提高自己的社会地位。

Mastery of computational techniques bestows special kinds of powers. These powers are at once cultural, political, and economic. On the cultural side, the coding elite dwells in the trustworthy world of numbers (Espeland & Stevens 1998, Golumbia 2009, Porter 1996). Because their formalisms are mathematically provable, the techniques appear universal and removed from the messy world of human politics (Agre 1997, Forsythe & Hess 2001, Ribes et al. 2019). The coding elite advances computation as the key to unlocking breakthroughs in practically every discipline (Hofman et al. 2017), including sociology (Watts 2014); to transforming every domain of government action (Fourcade & Gordon 2020, O'Reilly 2010); and generally to solving most problems facing human society (Morozov 2013). But only the initiated can penetrate their cryptic language (Burrell 2016), craft solutions to thorny problems through it, and improve their social status in the process.

在政治方面，编码精英栖身于强大的控制世界中。从狭义上讲，计算机科学家为了将社会规范和法律规则从人类语言转化为计算机代码而必须进行的解释工作不可避免地会引入扭曲和简化（Citron 2007）。但从广义上讲，“代码就是法律”（Lessig 2000）。代码统治，这意味着两件事。首先，代码使世界变得清晰易读（Scott 1999，Uliasz 2020）。它通过将人和物重构为可采取行动的机器可读实体来代表人和物（Amoore 2013，2020；Cheney -Lippold 2017；Johns 2021）。其次，代码具有强制执行作用。它像法律一样承认和排除、分离和分配。但是，纸面上规定的法律必须由单独的机构（通常是人类，因此能够行使自由裁量权）来执行，而代码既指定规则，又（一旦编译和运行）使其自动化。

On the political side, the coding elite dwells in the powerful world of control. In a narrow sense, the interpretive work that computer scientists must perform in order to translate social norms and legal rules from human language into computer code inevitably introduces distortions and simplifications (Citron 2007). But in a broader sense, “code is law” (Lessig 2000). Code governs, which means two things. First, code makes the world legible (Scott 1999, Uliasz 2020). It speaks for people and objects by reconstructing them into machine-readable entities that can be acted upon (Amoore 2013, 2020; Cheney-Lippold 2017; Johns 2021). Second, code enforces. It admits and excludes, separates and allocates in much the same way that law does. But whereas the law as specified on paper must be enforced by a separate body (generally human and therefore able to exercise discretion), code both specifies the rules and (once compiled and run) automates them.

在物质层面，编程精英们沉浸于利润丰厚的金钱世界。对于风险投资家来说，数字科技公司产品最引人注目之处在于其强大的扩展能力。例如，Facebook 迄今为止在全球拥有超过 26 亿用户，所有用户都自愿参与平台核心内容的创作。正如Morozov（2015）所说：“Facebook 的用户越多，它的价值就越大……搜索引擎也是如此：使用谷歌的人越多，它就越好，因为从某种意义上说，每次搜索都是对服务的一次调整和改进。” 第一个优势被称为网络效应。第二个优势是机器学习运作方式的直接结果：它由自动反馈循环驱动，不断吞噬新数据，逐步提高预测准确性（或至少是声称如此），从而增加市场潜力。

On the material side, the coding elite dwells in the profitable world of money. For venture capitalists, what is most compelling about the products of digital tech sector firms is how well they scale. For instance, Facebook to date has more than 2.6 billion users worldwide, all voluntarily producing the platform's core content. As Morozov (2015) puts it, “the more people on Facebook, the more valuable it becomes.… It's the same for search engines: the more people are using Google, the better it becomes, because every search is in some sense a tinkering and improvement in the service.” The first advantage is known as network effects. The second is a direct consequence of the way machine learning works: It is fueled by automated feedback loops, devouring new data continuously and incrementally improving predictive accuracy (or at least claiming to do so) and thus market possibilities.

信息技术的悠久历史或多或少是一种持续不断的驱动力，旨在完善控制——对劳动力的控制、对材料和市场变化的控制——其根源可以追溯到工业革命（Beniger 1989，Braverman 1974）。Burris （1989，1993 ）认为，这种内在趋势使得负责技术控制的专家阶层越来越独立于他们的官僚上司。计算机化的控制形式尤其如此，它倾向于扁平化社会等级制度、在专家和非专家部门之间形成组织两极分化以及技术职能和管理职能之间的融合。正如Burris（1989，第11页）所说，“展示出的专业知识和资历认证倾向于取代等级权威，成为合法权力的基本来源。”

The long history of information technology is a more or less continuous drive to refine control—control over labor, control over the vagaries of materials and markets—that finds its roots in the industrial revolution (Beniger 1989, Braverman 1974). Burris (1989, 1993) argues that this immanent tendency has made the class of experts tasked with technical control more and more autonomous from their bureaucratic masters. This is especially true of computerized forms of control, which tend to favor a flattening of social hierarchies, a polarization of organizations between expert and nonexpert sectors, and a convergence between technical and managerial functions. As Burris (1989, p. 11) puts it, “demonstrated expertise and credential certification tend to replace rank authority as the basic source of legitimate power.”

编码精英提供了此过程的下一次迭代。他们的权力几乎完全在于对技术的控制，而不是曾经定义职业管辖权的专业化制度化流程（Eyal 2013）。编码精英明显不屑于认证，他们广泛体现了这样一种观念，即技艺通过具体的应用来证明其价值。他们通过“更好更快地完成任务的纯粹能力”获得权力（Eyal 2013，第 869 页）。必要时，他们还依赖技术演示（Rosental 2013 ）中蕴含的“预言、奇观和承诺”（ Pardo-Guerra 2019 ）的吸引力。用Komisar（2000，第 93 页；另见Thrift 2000）的话来说，“是浪漫，而不是金钱，让这项事业值得追求。”由管理大师、专业杂志和技术传播者（负责传播对特定技术的信念并建立忠实的追随者）组成的文化圈进一步帮助组织这种神话的制造，并将权力集中到那些能够实施和理解代码的人以及资助他们的机构和个人手中。

The coding elite offers the next iteration of this process. Their power resides almost wholly in their control of technique as opposed to the institutional processes of professionalization that once defined occupational jurisdiction (Eyal 2013). Notably dismissive of credentialing, the coding elite broadly embodies the idea that craft proves its value through concrete application. They gain power through “the sheer capacity to accomplish [a] task better and faster” (Eyal 2013, p. 869). When necessary, they also rely on the allure of “prophecy, spectacle and promise” (Pardo-Guerra 2019) embedded in technical demonstrations (Rosental 2013). In the words of Komisar (2000, p. 93; also Thrift 2000), “it's the romance, not the finance, that makes the business worth pursuing.” A cultural circuit made of management gurus, specialized magazines, and tech evangelists (tasked with spreading belief in a particular technology and building a loyal following) further helps organize this myth-making and consolidate power into the hands of those able to implement and understand code and the institutions and individuals who fund them.

为了扩张市场，科技行业日益蚕食并霸占了那些曾经被视为专业判断专属领域（涵盖从企业管理、医疗、刑事司法系统到国防、教育和社会福利等各个领域）的领域。根深蒂固的司法管辖权和人类机构不过是暂时的妥协，等待着它们最常规的任务，有时甚至是整个工作领域被自动化取代。而且，无论多么声名显赫或准入门槛多么高，任何职业都无法避免其判断受到第二种（算法）意见的左右，甚至被其完全取代。合法性已经从专业人士手中转移到了“码王”手中，并且，越来越多地被算法所取代。

In its quest for market expansion, the tech industry increasingly carves away at and lays claim to tasks that once were protected as the proper domain of professional judgement in every occupation from business management, medicine, and the criminal justice system to national defense, education, and social welfare. Deeply entrenched jurisdictions and human institutions are nothing but transient compromises awaiting the automation of their most routine tasks and sometimes their entire work domain. And no profession, no matter how prestigious or how high the barriers to entry, is exempt from having its judgment subject to a second (algorithmic) opinion, if not wholly supplanted by it. Legitimacy has been displaced from the professional to the coder-king—and, increasingly, to the algorithm.

在挑战专业管辖权时，编码精英利用行为经济学或社会心理学的论点，通常依赖于人类决策者和算法工具之间的正式比较，但测试设计倾向于技术性。工程师们援引了大量文献，其中一些文献由行业媒体和主流媒体推广，这些文献表明，即使是享有最高声望的专业人士，在客观性或最佳决策测试中也会出错（例如，Ariely 2010、Kahneman 2013、Rachlinski & Wistrich 2017、Watts 2011、Volokh 2019）。针对这些失败，他们反对机器不知疲倦的一致性。与医生相比，“算法不需要睡眠，它们在凌晨 2 点和早上 9 点的警惕性是一样的”（Obermeyer & Emanuel 2016，第 1218 页）。在他们看来，海量数据（在某些情况下是专门为训练机器学习算法而生成的）的存在本身就使人类决策者力不从心（Obermeyer & Lee 2017）；相反，人们应该使用算法来改革自己有意识的推理实践（Christian & Griffiths 2016）。这里起作用的首要意识形态是“认为人类心智是脆弱和有缺陷的，导致非理性选择，而这些选择未能充分考虑替代方案的更广泛结构”（Zuboff 2019，第 343 页）。然而，在代码承诺驯服人类“不可预测、顽固和非理性”倾向（Andrejevic 2020，第 2 页）的背后隐藏着强大的经济激励，可以更好地预测或引导行为，以便人们可以生成更多数据或看到更多广告；在人们注册之前就满足他们的需求，从而促使他们进行新的购买；或者在长期资金不足的公共机构中站稳脚跟，这些机构渴望加快、简化和自动化流程；取代客户服务；或克服工作积压。

In their challenge to professional jurisdictions, the coding elite leverages arguments that draw on behavioral economics or social psychology, often relying on formal comparisons between human decision-makers and algorithmic tools, but in tests designed to favor the technical. Engineers call upon a burgeoning literature, some of it popularized by the trade press and mainstream media, showing that even professionals at the highest levels of prestige prove fallible on tests of objectivity or optimal decision-making (i.e., Ariely 2010, Kahneman 2013, Rachlinski & Wistrich 2017, Watts 2011, Volokh 2019). To these failures they oppose the indefatigable consistency of machines. Compared to physicians, “algorithms need no sleep, and their vigilance is the same at 2am as at 9am” (Obermeyer & Emanuel 2016, p. 1218). In their eyes, the very existence of mountainous quantities of data (in some cases specifically generated to train machine learning algorithms) renders human decision-makers inadequate (Obermeyer & Lee 2017); rather, people should use algorithms to reform their own conscious practices of reasoning (Christian & Griffiths 2016). The overarching ideology at work here is “the notion that human mentation is frail and flawed, leading to irrational choices that fail to adequately consider the wider structures of alternatives” (Zuboff 2019, p. 343). However, lurking beneath code's promise to tame the human tendency to be “unpredictable, recalcitrant, and otherwise irrational” (Andrejevic 2020, p. 2) are powerful economic incentives to better predict—or direct—behavior so people can produce more data or see more ads; provide for people's desires before they even register, so as to nudge them toward new purchases; or gain a foothold in perennially underfunded public agencies eager to speed up, streamline, and automate processes; replace customer service; or overcome work backlogs.

全世界的赛博人，分裂

编码精英手中权力的巩固也体现在他们从新旧工作中的工人身上榨取劳动的独特方法上。如果说工业资本主义通过对商品的盲​​目崇拜掩盖了劳动的存在，那么数字资本主义则通过对人工智能 (AI) 的盲目崇拜和伪装的自动化有意掩盖了劳动的存在。按需应用程序、搜索引擎、地图网站、社交媒体网站，甚至自动驾驶汽车和许多其他产品的平稳运行，都依赖于大量人类的集体智慧，这些人类在执行着“幽灵工作”（Gray & Suri 2019；另见Gillespie 2018、Roberts 2019）。这是因为，如果内容没有经过精心准备以供处理，如果结果没有经过检查和纠正缺陷，或者没有人完成所谓的“最后一英里”工作，大多数算法系统就无法正常运行。在拼车应用上匹配司机和乘车请求、为网页质量评分、修正数字地图、为视频添加标签和注释、仔细检查虚拟助手的回复、纠正偏见以及审核社交媒体帖子——所有这些工作，直到今天，都需要大量真人参与其中。在对人工智能的盲目崇拜背后，是一条由沉默不语、默默无闻的男男女女组成的全球数字装配线，他们通常在充满危险的环境中劳作，其中许多人生活在南半球的后殖民地地区。与编程精英相对立的是一个新的劳动阶层：网络世袭阶级。

The consolidation of power in the hands of the coding elite also comes into view through their distinctive methods of extracting labor from workers in both new and old jobs. If industrial capitalism concealed labor's existence through the fetishism of commodities, digital capitalism intentionally conceals it through the fetish of artificial intelligence (AI) and feigned automation. The smooth functioning of on-demand apps, search engines, mapping sites, social media websites, and even autonomous vehicles and many other products all depend on the collective intelligence of armies of humans performing ghost work (Gray & Suri 2019; also see Gillespie 2018, Roberts 2019). This is because most algorithmic systems cannot function adequately without content being carefully prepared for processing, without outcomes being checked and corrected for flaws, or without humans completing the so-called last-mile jobs. The work of matching drivers to ride requests on ridesharing apps, scoring web pages for quality, correcting digital maps, tagging and annotating videos, double-checking virtual assistants’ responses, correcting biases, and moderating social media postings 3 all demands, to this day, a multitude of real humans in the loop. What stands beneath the fetish of AI is a global digital assembly line of silent, invisible men and women, often laboring in precarious conditions, many in postcolonies of the Global South. A new class of workers stands opposite the coding elite: the cybertariat.

无论是小型初创企业还是大型企业，这些被束缚在算法系统日常运营中的劳动力都是一种负担。这是因为它们的估值和利润预测取决于其系统执行的所有任务能否尽可能完全自动化。例如，共享出行平台优步（Uber）曾斥巨资开发自动驾驶汽车，因为意识到劳动监管的威胁，这可能会迫使他们向司机支付更能维持生计的工资。然而，颇具启发性的是，在加州选民批准由行业发起的第22号提案后不久，该公司就放弃了这一计划。该提案将基于应用程序的司机归类为承包商，而非正式员工（这些正式员工可能会向公司施压，要求提供福利和更高的工资）。有时，人工招聘被视为权宜之计，但随着程序员不断突破自动化计算能力的极限，这种暂时性措施可能会成为永久性措施（Shestakofsky，2017）。工作平台化正在各个行业和整个组织层级中兴起，这使得企业能够将不确定性转移到外部劳动力身上。没有人是无懈可击的：技术也会渗透并降低管理角色的技能，例如出租车调度或轮班安排（例如，Brynjolfsson & McAfee 2014，Ford 2015）。

The existence of this labor force yoked into the day-to-day operations of algorithmic systems is a liability for small start-ups and large firms alike. This is because their valuations and profit projections rest on the feasibility of automating as fully as possible any and all of the tasks performed by their systems. For instance, the ridesharing platform Uber invested massively in developing automated vehicles in recognition of the threat of labor regulation that might force them to pay drivers a more livable wage. Revealingly, however, the company pulled back from this plan shortly after California voters approved industry-sponsored Proposition 22, which classified app-based drivers as contractors rather than employees (who could have pressured the company for benefits and higher wages). Sometimes the enrollment of humans is viewed as a temporary fix, but as programmers struggle with the computational limits of what can be automated, the temporary may become permanent (Shestakofsky 2017). The platformization of work is on the rise in every sector and throughout the organizational hierarchy, allowing firms to shift uncertainty onto an externalized labor force. No one is invulnerable: Technology also penetrates and deskills management roles, such as taxi dispatch or shift scheduling (e.g., Brynjolfsson & McAfee 2014, Ford 2015).

必须理解，这些重组和创新并非简单地旨在将传统的模拟任务数字化，或将其外包给更廉价且分布在全球的劳动力。相反，它们也是数字资本主义运作的内在因素和关键要素。正如工业品的生产导致了无产阶级的产生，数字产品（算法和人工智能）的生产也创造了“网络无产阶级”（Huws 2014），他们从事“一系列无偿、微偿和低薪的人类任务”（Casilli 2017，第 3934-35 页；另见Ettlinger 2016）。然而，它们与马克思等人所描述的工业无产阶级有着鲜明的差异。无产阶级在物理上共存，密集地分布在工厂中。数字仓库和点击农场有时具备这些特质，但这些特质越来越弱。随着众包平台的兴起，这些数字化不稳定无产阶级的成员越来越个体化，彼此之间也越来越孤立。事实上，他们的工作条件更类似于旧时的原始工业化外包制度，即计件工作制，即工人获得材料，然后在家中进行加工。对于赛博人而言，工作与家庭生活的界限也变得模糊。数字化劳动力的碎片化、其算法式（而非官僚式）的管理（Aneesh 2009），以及工作项目被分解成微任务，使得集体行动和团结变得困难（Irani & Silberman 2013，Gray & Suri 2019）。

It is important to understand that these reorganizations and innovations do not simply aim to digitize traditionally analog tasks or to outsource them to a cheaper and globally distributed workforce. Rather, they are also native and essential to the very operation of digital capitalism. Just as the production of industrial goods led to the making of the proletariat, so the production of digital goods (algorithms and AI) has created the “cybertariat” (Huws 2014) that performs “a continuum of unpaid, micropaid and poorly paid human tasks” (Casilli 2017, pp. 3934–35; see also Ettlinger 2016). However, differences with the industrial proletariat described by Marx and others are stark. The proletariat was physically copresent, densely packed in factories. Digital warehouses and click farms sometimes have these qualities, but increasingly less so. As crowdsourcing platforms take over, members of this digital precariat are more and more individualized and isolated from one another. In fact, their working conditions resemble more the old proto-industrial putting-out system, or piecework, by which laborers are supplied materials that they transform at home. For cybertarians, too, the lines between work and domesticity have blurred. The fragmentation of the digital workforce, its algocratic (rather than bureaucratic) management (Aneesh 2009), and the disaggregation of work projects into microtasks makes collective action and solidarity difficult (Irani & Silberman 2013, Gray & Suri 2019).

对于马克思和恩格斯来说，让无产阶级苦不堪言的是来自其他工人（产业后备军）以及技术本身的无时不在的竞争。对于网络无产阶级来说，这两种威胁都已完全内生化。首先，数字公司投资于通过平台扩大劳动力规模，并将其工作分解为无数的微任务，其目的也是为了支持这些劳动力的自主更替，Vertesi 等人 (2020)将此过程称为“前自动化”（另见Casilli & Posada 2019）。换句话说，平台同时利用自己不稳定的网络工作者执行无法轻易自动化的任务，并使用他们产生的数据来实现自动化（Shestakofsky 2017）。这些工作者在平台上和被宣传为人工智能的系统中劳动。他们的贡献被有意掩盖，许多购买他们服务的人的希望是，最终可以完全消除对这种人工计算的需求（Gray & Suri 2019）。其次，平台也加剧了劳动者之间的竞争，因为它允许某些职业（例如教师、文化表演者）大幅扩大其覆盖范围，从而可能最大限度地减少人力需求，并让赢家通吃的逻辑得以盛行。第三，平台化的劳动力，无论是线上还是线下，通常都由算法自行管理，以便根据市场状况、服务质量、物理距离或薪酬进行实时优化（Kellogg 等人，2020）。由此导致的工作体验不稳定——工作不确定、时间安排不规律、令人窒息的监视、持续的高风险审查和不稳定的工资——（Dubal 2017、Duffy 2020、Gregg 2018、Kalleberg & Vallas 2018、Levy & Barocas 2018、Rosenblat 2019、Schor 2020）引发了一系列社会病态，包括负面的健康后果（Schneider & Harknett 2019）。此外，工人可能会经历算法的残酷性，表现为由于算法规则的变化或跨越危险的阈值而导致命运突然逆转（Gray & Suri 2019）。例如，许多零工工人或内容提供者会因为评分或工作时间的下降而突然被切断与其主要收入来源平台的连接。重要的是，这种强制的劳动力灵活性也得到了该行业坚决反对劳动法规（如加州议会第 5 号法案）4 的支持，这些法规提议将平台工人视为雇员而不是独立承包商。

For Marx and Engels, what kept the proletariat miserable was the ever-present competition from other workers (the industrial reserve army) and that from technology itself. For the cybertariat, both threats have been fully endogenized. First, digital companies’ investments in scaling up a workforce via a platform and disaggregating its work into myriads of microtasks are also designed to support that workforce's autonomous replacement, a process Vertesi and coauthors (2020) call “pre-automation” (see also Casilli & Posada 2019). In other words, platforms are simultaneously using their own precarious cyber workers both to perform the tasks that cannot be easily automated and to use the data they produce to automate them (Shestakofsky 2017). These workers labor on platforms and within systems promoted as artificially intelligent. Their contributions are intentionally obscured, and the hope of many who buy their services is that the need for such human computation can eventually be eliminated altogether (Gray & Suri 2019). Second, platforms also magnify the competition among workers, by allowing certain occupations (e.g., teachers, cultural performers) to scale up their reach dramatically, possibly minimizing manpower needs and allowing a winner-take-all logic to take hold. Third, platformized workforces, whether on- or offline, are typically managed algorithmically themselves, so as to be optimized in real time for market conditions, service quality, physical distance or compensation (Kellogg et al. 2020). The resulting precarity in the experience of work—in the form of uncertain jobs, irregular schedules, suffocating surveillance, constant high-stakes reviews, and unstable wages—(Dubal 2017, Duffy 2020, Gregg 2018, Kalleberg & Vallas 2018, Levy & Barocas 2018, Rosenblat 2019, Schor 2020) leads to a host of social pathologies, including negative health outcomes (Schneider & Harknett 2019). In addition, workers may experience algorithmic cruelty in the form of sudden reversals of fortune caused by changing algorithmic rules or the crossing of a perilous threshold (Gray & Suri 2019). Many gig workers or content providers, for example, experience being suddenly cut off from platforms that were their primary source of income for a dip in their rating or worked hours. Importantly, this forced flexibility of labor is also buttressed by the industry's firm opposition to labor regulations (such as California's Assembly Bill 5) 4 that propose to treat platform workers as employees rather than independent contractors.

最后，赛博亚利安的边界并不仅限于廉价的平台化劳动力。数字资本主义的显著特征之一是其对免费劳动力的依赖。许多相关的分类和识别工作实际上是由无偿平台用户和微任务执行者完成的。正如Ekbia & Nardi (2017)所定义的那样，这种“异化”过程包括生成内容、群体解谜、提供反馈，或者仅仅是被追踪。特斯拉司机每次驾驶时都会训练公司的自动驾驶算法，就像我们每个人在完成“我不是机器人”的验证码测试以进入网站时一样。从这个意义上说，几乎每个人都属于赛博亚利安。历史学家尤瓦尔·哈拉里 (2017 ) 写道：“如果马克思今天复活，他可能会敦促他仅存的几位信徒少花点时间阅读《资本论》，多花点时间研究互联网和人类基因组。”现代马克思会指出，在21世纪，对资本而言，人的真正价值越来越不在于其劳动力和肉体，而在于某种更为私密、或许更接近其物种本质的东西：关于他们是谁、内心深处以及彼此之间如何联系的数百万条信息。他会在数十亿数字用户在线生活中进行的无偿点击劳动中发现新的剩余价值创造形式（Huws 2014 , Zuboff 2019）。他也会想要明确指出这种积累模式所特有的阶级对抗及其相关的意识形态斗争。

Finally, the boundaries of the cybertariat do not stop at the cheap, platformized workforce. One of the distinguishing features of digital capitalism is its reliance on free labor. Much of the relevant work of classification and identification is in fact performed by unpaid platform users and microtaskers. As defined by Ekbia & Nardi (2017), this process of “heteromation” includes generating content, crowd-puzzling over problems, providing feedback, or just being tracked. Tesla drivers train the company's autonomous driving algorithms every time they drive, as do we all when completing a captcha “I am not a robot” test to enter a website. In that sense, nearly everyone belongs to the cybertariat. Historian Yuval Harari (2017, p. 276) writes that “if Marx came back to life today, he would probably urge his few remaining disciples to devote less time to reading Das Kapital and more time to studying the Internet and the human genome.” A modern Marx would have remarked that in the twenty-first century, the real value, to capital, of a human being is located less and less in their labor power and physical body and increasingly in something much more intimate, perhaps closer to their species’ being: the millions of bits of information about who they are, deep down, and how they relate to one another. He would have identified new forms of surplus value generation in the unpaid clickwork that billions of digital users do as they go about their online lives (Huws 2014, Zuboff 2019). And he would have wanted to specify the class antagonisms and associated ideological struggles that are specific to this mode of accumulation.

那么集体动员和团结的可能性又如何呢？对赛博塔利亚特来说，像过去的无产阶级那样，通过进行车间组织来抵制对其劳动的榨取可能更加困难。他们工作状况的物质基础不允许这样做。尽管如此，抵抗仍在积极进行，例如在场外组织的在线论坛上。致力于赛博塔利亚特权利的程序员也发挥了作用，他们创建了工具来帮助赛博塔利亚特特人进行信息共享和自我组织。例如，巧妙的Turkopticon是一个网络浏览器插件，它覆盖了亚马逊Mechanical Turk平台的功能，帮助从事按任务付费点击工作的工人避免质量低劣的工作、延迟付款和直接的工资盗窃（Irani & Silberman 2013）。配套的Dynamo平台支持工人围绕这些问题进行集体组织（Salehi等人2015）。最后，过去的拖延和按章办事策略在职场算法博弈中再次出现（Kellogg等人，2020）。这些以及其他形式的算法行动主义，通过、对抗并超越盈利算法系统而发挥作用。

What about the possibilities for collective mobilization and solidarity? It may be more difficult for the cybertariat to resist the extraction of their labor by undertaking shop-floor organizing, as did the proletarians of the past. The material basis of their work situation precludes it. Resistance is actively underway nonetheless, for example, in online forums organized off-site. Coders allied to cyber workers' rights also play a role, creating tools to aid cybertarians in information sharing and self-organizing. The ingenious Turkopticon, for example, is a web browser plugin that overlays features on the Amazon Mechanical Turk platform, helping workers who do pay-per-task clickwork to avoid poor quality jobs, delayed payment, and outright wage theft (Irani & Silberman 2013). The companion Dynamo platform supports workers in collective organizing around these issues (Salehi et al. 2015). Finally, the foot-dragging and work-to-rule strategies of the past reemerge in the gaming of workplace algorithms (Kellogg et al. 2020). These and other forms of algoactivism work through, against, and outside of profit-making algorithmic systems.

传统的组织形式也在涌现，包括工会组建和争取实现工人保护立法的努力。举例来说，公平排班运动旨在规范和限制加剧工人不稳定性的工作排班软件的使用，并恢复他们对工作之外时间的控制。在洛杉矶，拼车公司的司机成立了“拼车司机联合会”，该组织目前在加利福尼亚州的成员数量正在增加，并在美国其他地区设立分会。最后，工人所有的平台已经成为主流企业平台的替代方案。现有的合作社提供库存照片集、易货和保姆互换以及流媒体音乐服务（Scholz & Schneider 2016）。这场平台合作主义运动旨在将不同职业和行业的高科技合作社联合成一个联盟，或者说是一种合作社的合作社。

Traditional forms of organizing are emerging as well, including labor union formation and efforts to realize worker protection legislation. The fair scheduling movement, to give one example, seeks to regulate and limit the use of shift allocation software that has exacerbated workers’ precarity and reinstate control over their time outside of work. In Los Angeles, drivers for ridesharing companies have formed Rideshare Drivers United, which is now growing its membership in California and opening chapters in other parts of the United States. Finally, worker-owned platforms have emerged as an alternative to the predominant corporate platforms. Existing co-ops offer stock photo collections, bartering and babysitting swaps, and streaming music services (Scholz & Schneider 2016). This movement for platform cooperativism seeks to link together high-tech co-ops across occupations and industries into a consortium, or a kind of co-op of co-ops.

编码精英们广泛的领域相关性主张从另一个根本上改变了组织流程：通过推进以技术效率和机械客观性为基础的治理逻辑（Porter 1996）。诚然，通过数字进行治理并不是什么新鲜事，它比计算机的出现早了几个世纪。算法思维模式（例如，通过决策树类型的结构）早已在刑事司法系统、金融和保险、劳动管理和教育领域得到广泛应用（Bouk 2015、Gandy 1993、Harcourt 2007、Lauer 2017）。新事物在于行为跟踪数据的使用，包括我们在设备上所做的事情以及我们环境中的设备捕获的关于我们的信息，以及对处理这些数据的计算能力的日益依赖。

The coding elite's expansive domain relevance claims have transformed organizational processes in another fundamental way: by advancing a logic of governance grounded in technical efficiency and mechanical objectivity (Porter 1996). To be sure, governance through numbers is not new and precedes the advent of computers by centuries. Algorithmic modes of thinking (for example, via decision tree–type structures) have long proliferated in the criminal justice system, finance and insurance, labor management, and education (Bouk 2015, Gandy 1993, Harcourt 2007, Lauer 2017). What is new is the use of behavioral trace data, including the things we do on devices and also things captured about us by devices in our environment, and the growing reliance on computing power to process these data.

种类繁多的海量数据使得某些现有算法变得更加强大。此外，一类新型算法（深度学习，神经网络模型的演变）通过从数据中直接推断来利用这种丰富性。虽然不能完全肯定这些算法能够自我编程，但它们确实能够以超越人类理解的方式进行自我优化。虽然这些技术的历史可以追溯到 20 世纪 50 年代，但它们真正腾飞是在 20 世纪 80 年代，当时它们开始在金融领域实施应用（MacKenzie 2018）。当今的学习算法嵌入在社交媒体信息流、工作场所监控系统、智慧城市、港口和边境以及现代战争中（例如，Amoore 2013、Green 2019、Russell 2019、Suchman 2020）。一个重要的结果是，许多常用来预测人类行为的模型现在可以随着新数据的输入而动态更新，从而能够通过控制论反馈回路进行持续调整。这些技术放大了Golumbia（2009）所称的计算主义的文化力量，即相信计算机能够并且必须支撑社会组织和资源分配的基本过程。

The sheer abundance of data of many varied kinds has allowed certain classes of algorithms already in existence to become much more powerful. Additionally, a new class of algorithms (deep learning, an evolution of neural network models) exploits this abundance by drawing direct inferences from the data. While it is not quite apt to suggest that these algorithms program themselves, they do self-optimize in ways that outpace human understanding. Although these techniques have a long history going back to the 1950s, they really took off in the 1980s, when applications started being implemented in finance (MacKenzie 2018). Today's learning algorithms are embedded in social media feeds, in workplace surveillance systems, in smart cities, at ports and borders, and in modern warfare (e.g., Amoore 2013, Green 2019, Russell 2019, Suchman 2020). One important consequence is that many models commonly used to predict people's actions can now be dynamically updated as new data come in, allowing for continuous adjustments to be made through cybernetic feedback loops. These techniques have magnified the cultural power of what Golumbia (2009) calls computationalism, or the belief that computers can and must underwrite fundamental processes of social organization and resource allocation.

上一节展示了编码精英如何通过将人类推理视为不充分的手段来巩固权力，即使是高级专业人士的专业决策也是如此。在编码精英看来，机器推理不仅速度更快、技术更优越，而且更公平、更公正。机械的、非人性化的流程优于植根于个人判断的流程，这种观念并非计算机时代的发明。一个多世纪以前，马克斯·韦伯就讨论过遵循“可计算的规则”并“不考虑个人”做出决策的专家型官员的崛起（Weber 1978，第 975 页）。他指出，官僚管理取代了领主管理，领主可能“被个人的同情和恩惠、恩典和感激所感动”。相比之下，任何接受官僚程序的人都会得到同样公正的考虑。事实上，官僚主义越是非人性化，就越是发展完善。它与资本主义市场经济齐头并进，要求“公共行政的官方事务必须准确、明确、连续、尽可能快速地完成”（韦伯 1978 年，第 974 页）。

The previous section showed how the coding elite consolidate power by framing human reasoning as inadequate, even the expert decision-making of high-status professionals. In the coding elite's judgment, machine reasoning is not only faster and technically superior but also more equitable and fairer. The notion that a mechanistic, impersonal process is superior to one rooted in the discretion of individuals is also not an invention of the computer age. Over a century ago, Max Weber discussed the rise of the expert functionary who follows “calculable rules” and decides “without regard for persons” (Weber 1978, p. 975). Bureaucratic administration, he noted, has displaced administration by lords who could be “moved by personal sympathy and favor, by grace and gratitude.” By contrast, anyone subject to a bureaucratic process receives the same impartial consideration. In fact, bureaucracy is more perfectly developed the more it is dehumanized. And it goes hand in hand with the capitalist market economy, which demands that the “official business of public administration be discharged precisely, unambiguously, continuously, and with as much speed as possible” (Weber 1978, p. 974).

将社会群体的历史数据纳入官僚机构规则驱动的流程，使得对未知个体的风险评估更加精确。这种精算主义被提升为一项崇高的目标，与一些进步思想相联系，即提供更公平的社会机构准入机会，改善被排斥群体的生活机会。例如，在信贷和保险等领域，包容性往往表现为积极的市场扩张，推动人们寻找此前未曾关注的群体的信息。随着客户群体的扩大和贷款业务变得更加公平，统计数据被引入，作为标准化决策标准和更好地管理不确定性的一种方式。通过普及信用报告和量化风险评估，建立了国家信托基础设施，使贷款机构更容易与未知借款人合作（Guseva & Rona-Tas 2001、Lauer 2017、Marron 2009）。与此同时，越来越多样化的数据可用性使得扩大与确定风险相关的变量范围成为可能，从而推动了风险评估从群体评估转向个体化（Harcourt 2007，Lauer 2017）。

The incorporation of historical data about social groups into the rule-driven processes of bureaucracy has allowed for more precise risk assessments about unknown individuals. This actuarialism was elevated to a noble purpose linked to progressive ideas about providing more equitable access to social institutions and improving the life chances of the excluded. In domains such as credit and insurance, for instance, inclusion often took the form of aggressive market expansion, driving the search for information on previously unseen populations. As customer pools grew and lending operations became more arms’ length, statistics were brought in as a way to both standardize decision-making criteria and better manage uncertainty. A national trust infrastructure was built through the generalization of credit reporting and the quantitative evaluation of risk, making it easier for lenders to work with unknown borrowers (Guseva & Rona-Tas 2001, Lauer 2017, Marron 2009). Meanwhile, the availability of increasingly varied data made it possible to expand the range of variables that were deemed relevant to the determination of risk, fueling a movement away from group assessment of risk and, increasingly, toward its individualization (Harcourt 2007, Lauer 2017).

不断变化的政治格局是推动精算方法在众多机构中受到青睐的另一个重要因素。20 世纪 70 年代新一轮的反歧视立法使得依赖人类判断变得越来越成问题。越来越多的证据表明，私人和公共决策者都经常屈从于模糊的直觉、个人偏见和武断的意见。这些决策被认为是不公平的，因为它们往往偏向低地位群体，或者根本不一致。因此，精算技术兴起的历史记载强调了人们不断努力要求机构承担责任，并纠正偏见、徇私和排斥的历史。现代算法的机制承诺透明以及在无知之幕之后的平等、冷静的对待，而不会基于种族或性别等被禁止的人口统计特征进行区分（Krippner 2017、Lauer 2017、Simon 1988）。例如，纽约市警察局当时开发的用于追踪和绘制犯罪地图的COMPSTAT系统，旨在通过使警务决策更加客观、更加数据化，从而减少歧视性警务实践（Didier，2013）。同样，洛杉矶警察局也采用了预测工具，以应对严重的合法性和问责制危机（Brayne，2020，第138页）。

The changing political landscape was another important factor driving the appeal of actuarial approaches across a wide range of institutions. A new wave of antidiscrimination legislation in the 1970s had made reliance on human judgment increasingly problematic. Evidence had accumulated that both private and public decision-makers were routinely giving into vague intuitions, personal prejudices, and arbitrary opinions. These decisions were deemed unfair in the sense that they were often skewed against low-status groups, or were simply inconsistent. Historical accounts of the rise of actuarial techniques thus emphasize progressive efforts to both demand accountability from institutions and redress histories of bias, favoritism, and exclusion. The mechanics of modern algorithms offered promises of transparency and of equal, dispassionate treatment—behind the veil of ignorance—without making distinctions based on prohibited demographic characteristics such as race or gender (Krippner 2017, Lauer 2017, Simon 1988). For instance, the COMPSTAT system for tracking and mapping crime developed by the New York City Police Department in this era was pitched as a way to reduce discriminatory policing practices by making policing decisions more objective and data driven (Didier 2013). Similarly, the Los Angeles Police Department adopted predictive tools as a response to a grave crisis of legitimacy and accountability (Brayne 2020, p. 138).

通过看似消除了人类的任意性，新的算法分类机制为程序公平提供了论据。然而，它可能无法满足公平的其他社会定义。学者们现在正在考虑这样一个事实，即算法系统既可能重现某些群体不平等，也可能创建新的社会等级制度（Barocas & Selbst 2016、Benjamin 2019、Eubanks 2017、Fourcade & Healy 2013、Gandy 1993、Noble 2018、O'Neill 2016）。算法（尤其是机器学习算法，它通过检测数据中的模式并将这些模式推广到新案例）产生不平等的机制与受规则约束的机构或直觉的人类决策者产生不平等的方式不同。最后，由于算法决策依赖于大量多维、复杂且通常专有的模型，因此它们也更加不透明且更难以挑战（Burrell 2016，Pasquale 2015）。

By seemingly eliminating human arbitrariness, the new regime of algorithmic classification lends itself to an argument for procedural fairness. However, it may not satisfy other social definitions of fairness. Scholars are now reckoning with the fact that algorithmic systems may both reproduce certain group inequalities and create new social hierarchies (Barocas & Selbst 2016, Benjamin 2019, Eubanks 2017, Fourcade & Healy 2013, Gandy 1993, Noble 2018, O'Neill 2016). The mechanisms by which an algorithm—particularly a machine learning algorithm, which operates by detecting patterns in data and generalizing from those patterns to novel cases—produces inequality are different from the ways a rule-bound institution or an intuitive human decision-maker does so. Finally, because algorithmic decisions depend on massively multi-dimensional, complex, and often proprietary models, they are also more opaque and harder to challenge (Burrell 2016, Pasquale 2015).

算法不等式

在韦伯式的分析框架中，最终塑造阶级（或阶级境况）形成的，是资产和机会在一系列制度领域内及跨领域的社会分配方式。只要计算机算法分配奖励、机会或惩罚，它们就有能力改变个人的人生机遇（Fourcade & Healy 2013）。算法机制明确而理性地完成这种分配工作，并且凭借其高效的扩展能力，增加了可能进行分配的场所数量。然而，通过这样做，它们隐性地重塑了社会阶级形成的过程。与根植于纳入与排除（例如，能够获得信贷的人与被排除在信贷之外的人）的明确界限的传统守门机制不同，新的算法机制产生了一种分类境况的滑动尺度，对位置的区分更加细致（Fourcade & Healy 2013）。例如，信用风险评估良好的优质借款人享有优厚的信贷合同，不良借款人则面临高利贷的合同，而处于两者之间的借款人则获得一系列或多或少有利的条件（Cottom 2017，Poon 2009）。数字化并非完全排斥，反而可能助长各种形式的掠夺性包容。由于这些包容往往给少数族裔带来不平等的负担，人们熟悉的种族资本主义流程正在数字时代被重塑（Cottom 2020）。

In a Weberian analytical frame, what ultimately shapes the making of classes (or class situations) is the way that assets and opportunities are socially distributed within and across a range of institutional domains. Wherever computational algorithms distribute rewards, opportunities, or punishments, they have the capacity to alter the life chances of individuals (Fourcade & Healy 2013). Algorithmic mechanisms do this work of allocation explicitly and rationally, and through their capacity to scale efficiently, they also increase the number of sites where it might take place. By doing so, however, they implicitly rework the process of social class-making. Unlike traditional mechanisms of gatekeeping rooted in bright lines of inclusion versus exclusion (e.g., those who can obtain credit versus those excluded from it), new algorithmic mechanisms produce a sliding scale of classification situations with a much more fine-grained differentiation of positions (Fourcade & Healy 2013). For instance, desirable borrowers with favorable assessments of credit risk enjoy generous credit contracts, undesirable borrowers face deeply usurious ones, and those situated in between receive a panoply of more or less favorable offers (Cottom 2017, Poon 2009). Instead of complete exclusion, digitality may thus facilitate various forms of predatory inclusion. As these often exact an unequal burden on ethno-racial minorities, familiar processes of racial capitalism are being reinvented for the digital era (Cottom 2020).

理论上，算法分配被认为是完全准确和公平的，但在实践中却存在一些不足。一个关键问题是，程序员和模型构建者很少质疑他们使用的输入数据的质量（Broussard 2018、O'Neill 2016），尽管模型构建中的数据质量问题已开始得到解决（参见Gebru 等人 2018）。许多训练数据集的制作并没有太多关注不同群体的代表性或从用户或通过众包平台雇用的工人那里获得的注释的质量。例如，广泛用于训练面部识别系统的数据集导致了整个领域的错误和偏见的传播（Hanna 等人 2020、Noble 2018）。同样，众所周知，警务数据存在偏差，但它们通常用于预测警务的数据模型，就好像它们是了解犯罪行为的透明窗口一样。但事实并非如此。社会学家早就知道，警方报告很可能反映出机构的自我表现，这些表现与现实存在系统性偏差（Bittner & Garfinkel 1984），或者反映出个人和集体为规避官僚基准和指标而采取的策略（Lande & Mangels 2017）。机器学习系统的特定技术要求可能会进一步加剧这些问题。例如，为了提高预测能力，需要使用大型数据集，这促使人们将低级别犯罪（如公共场所饮酒或闲逛）纳入训练数据集。正如O'Neill（2016）所指出的，其结果是，模型恰恰根据那些很可能是警务实践的产物而非犯罪评估的轻微违法行为来形成风险预测。

Algorithmic allocations are envisioned in theory to be perfectly accurate and fair, but they fall short in practice in several ways. A key problem is that coders and model builders rarely question the quality of the input data they use (Broussard 2018, O'Neill 2016), although the problem of data quality in model-building is starting to be addressed (see Gebru et al. 2018). Many training data sets were produced without much attention to the representativeness of different groups or the quality of annotations obtained from users or from workers hired through crowdsourcing platforms. For instance, data sets widely used to train facial recognition systems contributed to the propagation of errors and prejudices throughout the field (Hanna et al. 2020, Noble 2018). Likewise, policing data are notoriously skewed, yet they are commonly used in data models for predictive policing as though they were a transparent window into criminal behavior. They are not. Sociologists have long known that police reports are likely to reflect institutional self-presentations that depart systematically from reality (Bittner & Garfinkel 1984) or individual and collective strategies to work around bureaucratic benchmarks and metrics (Lande & Mangels 2017). Specific technical requirements of machine learning systems may compound these problems further. For instance, the need for large data sets to improve predictive power has created an incentive to include low-level crimes (like drinking in public or loitering) in training data sets. The result, as O'Neill (2016) notes, is models that form risk predictions based on precisely those minor transgressions that are likely to be an artifact of policing practices rather than assessments of criminality.

决策中精算逻辑的一个关键前提是“相信过去观察到的模式可以为未来可能发生的活动和事件提供有用信息”（Gandy 2016，第 9 页）。但在人类事务中，根据过去预测未来可能会使机构现有的不平等待遇具体化和重现。由于人们对数据收集引擎的可见性是社会组织的，数字编码成为种族、性别和阶级结构熟悉运作的新渠道（Benjamin 2019）。因此，对有色人种社区的过度监管，加上制度化的种族定性做法，产生的犯罪数据集严重偏向这些群体（Jefferson 2020）。社会服务资格的自动化将最脆弱的家庭定为犯罪，并使他们无法享受应有的福利（Eubanks 2017）。相反，在以白人或男性为主的数据集上训练的算法可能根本看不到占主导地位的群体。一个基于机器学习的算法在审查求职者时，发现了亚马逊不成比例地雇佣男性的模式，并对那些包含暗示求职者是女性的申请给出了低分。

A key premise that justifies an actuarial logic in decision-making is “the belief that patterns observed in the past provide useful information about activities and events that may take place in the future” (Gandy 2016, p. 9). But in human matters, predicting the future on the basis of the past threatens to reify and reproduce existing inequalities of treatment by institutions. Because people's visibility to data collection engines is socially organized, digital coding becomes a new conduit for the familiar operations of the race, gender, and class structures (Benjamin 2019). Thus, the overpolicing of communities of color, combined with institutionalized practices of racial profiling, produces crime data sets skewed to severely overrepresent these groups (Jefferson 2020). The automation of social services eligibility criminalizes the most vulnerable families and diverts them from the benefits to which they are entitled (Eubanks 2017). Conversely, algorithms trained on mostly White or mostly male data sets might not see the dominated groups at all. A machine learning–based algorithm reviewing job applicants famously picked up on Amazon's pattern of disproportionately hiring men and gave low scores to applications containing signals that indicated the candidate was a woman.

预测系统的其他缺陷与构思不当或应用不当有关。虽然有人声称使用算法可以使决策变得更加客观，但这些系统中内置的目标函数通常反映其他目标，特别是机构成本优化和风险最小化。例如，一个旨在优化医疗支出的医疗风险评估模型低估了黑人患者病情的严重程度，而黑人患者平均使用的医疗资源较少，导致健康状况更差（Obermeyer等人，2019 年）。5值得注意的是，动态改进机器学习模型的过程也可能产生破坏性的反馈循环（O'Neill，2016 年）。例如，预测的高犯罪率地区或高风险个体将受到警方更多关注，导致更多逮捕，进而导致更严格的审查。Harcourt （2007）将这种强化审查循环命名为棘轮效应。同样，预测信用违约率的上升会导致黑人借款人的平均贷款条件大幅下降，从而可能导致更多违约。此外，过多地卷入刑事司法系统以及不良信用记录都会带来其他社会成本，包括就业、教育或住房障碍，所有这些都会导致进一步的财务损失（Alexander，2012）。预测分析的这种“涡轮性能”（Rona-Tas，2017）创造了一种自我实现的预言，即使在没有任何歧视意图的情况下，也会重现历史上的劣势和结构性不平等。

Other pitfalls of predictive systems have to do with poor conception or misapplication. While the use of algorithms is justified by claims that it makes decision-making more impersonal, the objective functions built into these systems often reflect other goals, particularly institutional cost optimization and risk minimization. For example, a medical risk assessment model programmed to optimize healthcare spending underestimates the severity of the condition of Black patients, who on average utilize fewer healthcare resources, leading to worse health outcomes (Obermeyer et al. 2019). 5 Notably, the processes through which machine learning models are dynamically refined can also produce a damaging feedback loop (O'Neill 2016). For instance, predicted high-crime areas or high-risk individuals will receive more police attention, leading to more arrests and, in turn, still more scrutiny. Harcourt (2007) names this reinforcing cycle of scrutiny the ratcheting effect. Similarly, higher rates of predicted credit defaults cause lending conditions to be much less favorable on average for Black borrowers, likely causing more defaults. Furthermore, disproportionate entanglement in the criminal justice system and a poor credit record both have other social costs, including barriers to employment, education, or housing, all of them resulting in further financial harm (Alexander 2012). This turboperformativity of predictive analytics (Rona-Tas 2017) creates a self-fulfilling prophecy, reproducing historical disadvantage and structural inequality even in the absence of any discriminatory intent.

最后，这些形式的劣势可能更难在政治上提出异议。由于它们是通过衡量个人而非群体行为来体现的，因此被认为是公平的。而且，由于它们体现在数学公式中，它们“被推广并被认为比前一个时代的歧视性制度更客观或更进步”（Benjamin 2019，第5页），因此可能更难被发现和挑战（Burrell 2016）。但正如Harcourt（2007）指出的那样，将正义（和惩罚）简化为计算模型从根本上是有问题的。对未来犯罪行为的预测过度决定了决策，使其超越了威慑、意图和伤害程度等其他考虑因素。这相当于对刑事司法的“认识论扭曲”（Harcourt 2007，第22页）。

Finally, these forms of disadvantage may be harder to contest politically. Because they are channeled through the measurement of individual, rather than group, behavior, they are perceived to be fair. And because they are embodied in mathematical formulas, they are “promoted and perceived as more objective or progressive than the discriminatory systems of a previous era” (Benjamin 2019, p. 5) and may thus be harder to see and to challenge (Burrell 2016). But as Harcourt (2007) points out, reducing justice (and punishment) to a computational model is fundamentally problematic. The prediction of future criminality overdetermines decision-making above other considerations such as deterrence, intent, and magnitude of harm. This amounts to an “epistemic distortion” of criminal justice (Harcourt 2007, p. 22).

公平可能是当今机器学习中最热门的话题，这常常引发关于哪种统计标准最适合具体情况的复杂争论：假阴性还是假阳性，人口统计平价还是预测利率平价（Weinberger 2019，Narayanan 2019）。一些批评家断然否认数学客观性本质上比人类判断更能防止社会不公平的说法，无论后者多么主观。Eubanks （2017，第 168 页）坚持同理心在提供社会服务中的根本性作用：“认为人类决策不透明且难以理解，就等于承认我们放弃了试图相互理解的社会承诺。” Pasquale（2019）呼应了这种观点（并颠覆了马克斯·韦伯的观点），得出结论，人治比机器治更能保障正当法律程序。

Fairness may be the most hotly debated topic in machine learning today, which often leads to complex arguments about which statistical criterion best fits the situation: false negatives versus false positives, or demographic parity versus predictive rate parity (Weinberger 2019, Narayanan 2019). Some critics reject outright the claim that mathematical objectivity is inherently better at guarding against social inequities than human judgement, however subjective the latter may be. Eubanks (2017, p. 168) insists on the fundamental role of empathy in the delivery of social services: “the assumption that human decision-making is opaque and inaccessible is an admission that we have abandoned a social commitment to try to understand each other.” Echoing this sentiment (and turning Max Weber on his head), Pasquale (2019) concludes that a rule of persons is better able to guarantee legal due process than a rule of machines.

算法统治

被纳入某些身份识别数据库长期以来一直是现代公民身份的先决条件（Koopman 2019；Lyon 2009、2015），但数字化放大了消除欺诈并以更细致的方式定制公民条款和福利的愿望（Fourcade 2021）。这一趋势是全球性的：信息现代化可能看起来异常熟悉，同时又在不同的政治和历史背景下截然不同。在印度，Aadhaar 是一种集成的身份识别系统，它存储每个公民的指纹和虹膜扫描以及人口统计数据，最初被宣传为一种消除腐败和有效提供福利服务的工具。它迅速成为与公共和私人机构互动的必需品，为新兴的大规模监控基础设施奠定了基础（Rao & Nair 2019）。在南非，后种族隔离政府同样寻求实施全国性的生物识别系统，以提高社会福利补助金支付的统一性。政府以典型的韦伯式风格声称，该系统的普遍性和标准化保证了平等对待（Donovan 2015）。尽管该国历史上信息基础设施一直具有压迫性，其中最臭名昭著的是其存折系统，但这个新的公民数据库还是受到了后种族隔离时代领导人的欢迎。6

Inclusion into some identification database has long been a prerequisite of modern citizenship (Koopman 2019; Lyon 2009, 2015), but digitality has magnified the ambition to eliminate fraud and also tailor the terms and benefits of citizenship in ever more fine-grained ways (Fourcade 2021). This trend is global: Informational modernization can look eerily familiar and, at the same time, strikingly different across political and historical contexts. In India, Aadhaar, an integrated identification system that stores fingerprint and iris scans along with demographic data for each citizen, was originally publicized as a tool for graft elimination and the efficient delivery of welfare services. It has swiftly become required for interactions with both public and private institutions, anchoring an emergent mass surveillance infrastructure (Rao & Nair 2019). In South Africa, the postapartheid government similarly sought to implement a nationwide biometric identification system to improve the uniformity of social welfare grant disbursement. In typical Weberian fashion, the government claims that the system's universalism and standardization guarantee equal treatment (Donovan 2015). Despite the country's history of oppressive information infrastructures, most notoriously its passbook system, this new citizen database was embraced by postapartheid leaders. 6

在中国，各市政府和中央政府都与私营企业合作，开发社会信用体系，旨在改善个人和组织的财务行为和公民意识（Ahmed 2019、Liu 2019、Ohlberg 等人 2017）。通过将算法生成的社会信用评分与切实的成果（便利和福利、公开表扬或羞辱）联系起来，这些体系促进了规则遵守（例如，使用人行横道过马路）和对社会期望的服从（例如，照顾父母、做志愿者工作）。虽然西方评论家经常从中国政治威权主义的角度来解读社会信用的发展，但我们应该记住，其他地方的私人数据基础设施也可能让人感到类似的压抑和无法逃避。例如，奥尼尔（O'Neill，2016）描述了一位求职者在美国零售业的很大一部分中被拒之门外，因为他未能通过一家与整个行业都有合同的软件公司设计的招聘预筛选测试。其他数据系统则普遍跨越国界运行。例如，自动识别欺诈行为的网络安全工具中内置的以欧洲为中心的假设，已成为全球基础设施中无处不在的一部分（Jonas & Burrell，2019）。

In China, both municipalities and the central government have partnered with private sector firms to develop social credit systems oriented to improving the financial behavior and civic-mindedness of individuals and organizations (Ahmed 2019, Liu 2019, Ohlberg et al. 2017). By linking algorithmically produced social credit scores to tangible outcomes (conveniences and perks, public praising or shaming), these systems foster rule compliance (e.g., using crosswalks to cross the street) and obedience to social expectations (e.g., taking care of one's parents, doing volunteer work). While Western commentators have often interpreted the development of social credit through the lens of China's political authoritarianism, it is useful to remember that private data infrastructures elsewhere can feel similarly oppressive and inescapable. O'Neill (2016) describes, for example, how a job applicant was shut out of work in a sizeable portion of the American retail industry when he failed a hiring prescreening test designed by a software company with contracts throughout the sector. Other data systems operate ubiquitously across national borders. Euro-centric assumptions built in to cybersecurity tools that automate the identification of fraud, for example, have become a ubiquitous part of the global infrastructure (Jonas & Burrell 2019).

在这些例子中，公平分配并不是唯一的问题。那些被如此强力统治的人无力塑造算法统治的条款，也无法逃避代码的规则，这引发了关于民主和人类自主性的根本问题（Amoore 2020，Aneesh 2009）。编码精英将其方法框定为普遍的和非特定领域的（Ribes 等人 2019）。但是，依赖单一逻辑来塑造跨机构的结果，可能会使人们陷入自我强化的排斥循环，影响他们整个社会存在的各个方面——包括工作、信贷、教育、住房和社会权利（Fourcade & Healy 2013，Rona-Tas 2017）。相比之下，不同的决策逻辑为那些数据资料显示他们在某些特别突出的领域（例如个人理财）是不可预测或没有前途的候选人的人创造了机会。7这也许就是为什么美国监管机构对让汽车保险公司使用信用评分来预测事故风险持谨慎态度，以及为什么雇主同样谨慎对待信用报告数据，寻找糟糕数字背后的人性故事（Kiviat 2019a、b）。

In these examples, fair allocation is not the only issue. The inability of those so forcefully governed to shape the terms of the algorithmic dominion, or to evade the rule of the code, raises fundamental questions about democracy and human autonomy (Amoore 2020, Aneesh 2009). The coding elite frames its approach as universal and domain nonspecific (Ribes et al. 2019). But reliance on a unitary logic to shape outcomes across institutions has the potential to trap people into self-reinforcing cycles of exclusion across the whole range of their social existence—including jobs, credit, education, housing, and social rights (Fourcade & Healy 2013, Rona-Tas 2017). Varying decision logics, by comparison, create openings and opportunities for those whose data profiles register them as unpredictable or unpromising candidates in some particularly salient domain (such as personal finance). 7 This is perhaps why regulators in the United States are wary about letting car insurers use credit scores to predict accident risk and why employers similarly tread carefully around credit reporting data, looking for the human story behind bad numbers (Kiviat 2019a,b).

被一个麻木不仁、毫无感情的系统统治——或者说推翻——似乎违反了人类尊严和自主的一些基本概念。与此相呼应，欧盟的《通用数据保护条例》规定了要求人工审查算法决策的解释权（Jones，2017）。同样，大量民族志文献表明，人们在工作生活中默默地抵制算法的权威。在美国，人们在对抗“算法老板”的斗争中取得了重要的法律胜利。在英国，人们因使用机器学习来确定 2020 年大学招生周期的学生安置而爆发了抗议活动，伦敦自治市议会放弃了“使用计算机算法帮助做出福利索赔和其他福利问题的决策”（Marsh，2020）。这些民众反抗的例子与大量的民族志证据相吻合，这些证据表明，配备算法工具的专业人士也经常表达怀疑，并在日常工作中推翻或忽视这些工具（Brayne 2017、2020；Christin 2017、2020；O'Neill 2016）。8

Being ruled—or overruled—by an insensate and affectless system seems to violate some fundamental notion of human dignity and autonomy. Echoing these sentiments, the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation instituted a right to an explanation that requires a human review of algorithmic decisions (Jones 2017). Similarly, a burgeoning ethnographic literature suggests that people quietly resist the authority of algorithms in their working lives. Important legal victories have been won against “algorithmic bosses” in the United States. In the United Kingdom, protests erupted over the use of machine learning to determine student placements in the 2020 university admissions cycle, and London borough councils went back on their “use of computer algorithms in helping to make decisions on benefit claims and other welfare issues” (Marsh 2020). These examples of popular resistance dovetail with the extensive ethnographic evidence showing that professionals outfitted with algorithmic tools also routinely express skepticism and override or ignore them in their day-to-day work (Brayne 2017, 2020; Christin 2017, 2020; O'Neill 2016). 8

最后，算法系统及其倡导者冒着助长一种危险迷信的风险，这种迷信曾被冯·哈耶克（1989）批判，即只有可衡量的事物才是重要的。根据算法系统的技术能力来构建一个社会的规范或法律真理，可能会让我们对不可衡量但至关重要的过程视而不见（阿甘本，2014），导致我们关注错误的结果，或产生得不偿失的社会成本（克劳福德，2021，埃斯佩兰和索德，2016）。尤其是，一心一意地关注狭隘任务的预测准确性，而这些任务又受限于可用数据和可提交分类的数据，这会限制政治或伦理主张的表达。正如甘迪（Gandy，2016，第 8 页）所言，在数字社会中，“对风险的担忧已经取代了我们对发现美好生活本质的兴趣，取而代之的是试图识别和控制那些可能使美好生活遥不可及的事物”。因此，正确的批判必须首先认识到算法是伦理政治实体，它们会产生自己的“关于善、违法和社会应有的样子的想法”（Amoore，2020，第 7 页）。换句话说，算法正在改变我们道德直觉的本质——即我们与自我和他人关系的本质——以及存在于社会中的意义。下一节将探讨这一不断变化的领域。

Finally, algorithmic systems and their advocates run the risk of propelling the dangerous superstition, once denounced by von Hayek (1989), that only what is measurable is important. Framing a society's normative or legal truths according to the technical capabilities of algorithmic systems may blind us to nonmeasurable but essential processes (Agamben 2014), cause us to focus on the wrong outcomes, or generate social costs that are not worth the payoff (Crawford 2021, Espeland & Sauder 2016). In particular, the single-minded focus on predictive accuracy on narrow tasks, circumscribed by the data that are available and what can be submitted to classification, curtails what political or ethical claims can be articulated. As Gandy (2016, p. 8) remarks, in the digital society, “concern about risk has come to replace our interest in discovering the essence of the good life with an attempt to identify and control those things that threaten to put it out of reach.” A proper critique must thus begin with the recognition that algorithms are ethico-political entities that generate their own “ideas of goodness, transgression and what society ought to be” (Amoore 2020, p. 7). In other words, algorithms are transforming the very nature of our moral intuitions—that is, the very nature of our relations to self and others—and what it means to exist in the social world. The next section examines this shifting terrain.

 
分类器及其不满
