专家系统，无论是人类的还是机械的，总是对与其交互的普通人提出要求：人们必须让自己清晰易懂，否则系统将无法识别他们，他们在与系统交互时必须遵守规则，而且他们质疑决策的能力通常有限。在传统的官僚机构中，这些过程的最终仲裁者几乎总是人类（Weber，1978）。但随着技术日益自主，人类处理器和决策者逐渐退居幕后，甚至这些步骤也可能由机器引导（Ellul，1967）。Andrejevic （2020）认为，通过迫使人们对自己进行预处理——将信息、想法、身份和交互标准化和碎片化，以便机器可读——计算机运作着一种社会去技能化的形式。编码精英们并没有让机器增强人类的智能，而是重新组织社会活动，让人类支持计算机的运行。因此，从某种意义上说，是人类被自动化了。

Expert systems, whether human or mechanical, always place demands on laymen who interact with them: People must make themselves legible or the system will not recognize them, they have to follow rules when interacting with it, and their ability to question decisions is often limited. In traditional bureaucracies, the final arbiter of these processes is almost always a human being (Weber 1978). But as technology becomes increasingly autonomous and human processors and decision-makers recede into the background, even these steps may become guided by machines (Ellul 1967). Andrejevic (2020) suggests that, by forcing people to preprocess themselves—to standardize and fragment messages, ideas, identities and interactions so as to be machine readable—computers operate a form of social deskilling. Instead of making machines augment human intelligence, the coding elite reorganizes social activities to make humans support the operation of computers. It is thus humans who are, in a certain sense, automated.

具体来说，将人类生活压缩成比特包，将经验流通过执行分类功能的算法进行过滤，这意味着什么？我们习惯于认为，当代算法分类器所实现的分类情况仅在某些关键时刻有效——例如，在申请贷款时允许进行信用检查。但数字基础设施的运作方式日益全面、持续和动态。数字数据痕迹不仅允许远离数据原始收集地点的机构进行侵入式探测（例如，信用数据对房东和潜在的恋爱对象至关重要，而警察局则渴望获得社交媒体数据），而且还可以通过实时运行的反应式控制论反馈回路来引导或控制行为。人们与数字系统的互动越多，其个人和社会生活的进程就越依赖于算法的运作和选择。这不仅适用于上述重大决策，也适用于日常的、时时刻刻的行为：例如，每次在线点击都可能揭示某种潜在趋势，或预示着与先前基线的偏离。随着新数据的涌入，类别和分类会发生动态调整，计算系统基于这些类别采取的操作也会随之调整。这对于人们最终如何看待自己以及社会身份的形成具有重要意义。

What does it mean, concretely, for human life to be condensed into packs of bits, for the flow of experience to be filtered through algorithms that perform a classifying function? We are used to thinking that the classification situations implemented through contemporary algorithmic classifiers only matter at certain key moments—for example, when allowing a credit check in order to apply for a loan. But the digital infrastructure operates in increasingly totalizing, continuous, and dynamic ways. Not only do digital data traces allow for intrusive probing by institutions far afield from the data's original collection site (e.g., credit data matter to landlords and to prospective romantic partners, and police departments are hungry for social media data), but they also enable the guiding or control of behavior through reactive, cybernetic feedback loops that operate in real time. The more one interacts with digital systems, the more the course of one's personal and social life becomes dependent on algorithmic operations and choices. This is true not only for the kinds of big decisions mentioned above but also for mundane, moment-by-moment actions: For instance, each online click potentially reveals some underlying tendency or signals a departure from a previous baseline. As new data flow in, categories and classifications get dynamically readjusted, and so do the actions that computing systems take on the basis of those categories. This has important implications for how people ultimately perceive themselves and for how social identities are formed.

身份的调节

在当今的数据提取和分析系统中，个体属性通常是根据行为痕迹推断出来的。每个有血有肉、有形有体的人都有一个由这些痕迹构成的“数据替身”——一个监控集合，其组成部分“在众多不同的计算中心循环流动”（Haggerty & Ericson 2000，第 611 页）。这些个人行为的“部分”已经获得了金融产品的流动性，可以进行交易和共享，以进行预测分析（Cohen 2019，第 67 页）。即使是那些曾经被认为是固定或几乎不变的身份特征——性别、种族、公民身份、国籍——也通过这种虚拟化的方式变得可读。例如，可以通过挖掘网页浏览和其他数字活动的模式来确定一个人可能是女性还是男性。但这些评估（另一组由算法得出的分类情况）始终是灵活且临时的，取决于流入的数据和特定的分类器组合。因此，性别认同的算法推断可能随时发生变化。技术将建立在更广泛的文化转变之上，并促进这种转变，使性别认同可能越来越多地被视为多元且流动的，而非二元且稳定的。

In today's systems of data extraction and analysis, properties of the individual are often inferred from behavioral traces. Each flesh and blood, embodied person has a “data double” made of these traces—a surveillant assemblage whose components, “circulate in a host of different centers of calculation” (Haggerty & Ericson 2000, p. 611). These “tranches” of individual behavior have acquired the liquidity of financial products and can be traded and shared for predictive profiling (Cohen 2019, p. 67). Even those aspects of identity once thought fixed or almost unchanging—gender, race, citizenship, nationality—become readable in this virtualized way. For instance, patterns of web browsing and other digital activities can be mined to determine whether one is likely to be a woman or a man. But these assessments (another set of algorithmically derived classification situations) are always flexible and provisional, depending on data flowing in and on the particular combination of classifiers. Consequently, the algorithmic inference of gender identity may change at any moment. Technology, then, builds on and feeds into a broader cultural shift by which gender identity may be increasingly experienced as multiple and fluid rather than binary and stable.

切尼-利波尔德（Cheney-Lippold，2017）在德勒兹（Deleuze）的理论基础上，指出算法身份具有调制性；也就是说，从行为轨迹中衍生出的属性会不断变化和修正。德勒兹（1992）所称的控制的模块化取代了纪律的僵化，后者将每个主体都塑造成同一个模子——流水线工人、经理、家庭主妇。关于我们的推断通常会以可视化、评估、分数或建议的形式反馈给我们，进而实时地重塑我们对自身的理解。即使是差异——例如生理年龄与算法年龄之间的差异，或者性别自我认同与算法性别之间的差异——也可能不再被不完善的技术系统视为有趣的错误，而是被解读为外部的、客观的、不断变化的信号，告知我们我们到底是谁。它们甚至可能通过自我强化的反馈过程（例如投放特定类型的广告或返回特定搜索结果）帮助我们加强与被测类型的主观关联。

Building on Deleuze, Cheney-Lippold (2017) notes that algorithmic identities have the quality of modulation; that is, the attributes derived from behavioral traces are continually subject to change and revision. The modularity of what Deleuze (1992) calls control supplants the rigidity of discipline, which cast each subject in the same mold—the assembly line worker, the manager, the housewife. Inferences made about us are often fed back to us as visualizations, assessments, scores, or recommendations and, in turn, reconfigure how we understand ourselves in real time. Even discrepancies—for instance, between biological age and algorithmic age or between gender self-identification and algorithmic gender—may come to be taken not as amusing mistakes by an imperfect technical system but as external, objective, and constantly fluctuating signals informing us of who we really are. They may even help tighten subjective associations with the measured types through self-reinforcing feedback processes (by serving certain kinds of ads or returning certain search results).

虽然算法可以将我们生活中的真相外化和调节化，改变“我们在世界上定位的感觉”（Arendt 2006，第 252 页），但它们不太可能从根本上改变性别或种族等主要结构形态在世界上的运作方式，正如我们在“精算主义及其不满”一节中所讨论的那样。相反，当用于使创造性表达和自我实验（例如围绕性；参见Hawgood 2020）合法化或改革机构分类系统时，可衡量类型的力量可能最强大。例如，斯诺登的披露显示，美国政府通过国家安全局试图从数字痕迹中推断公民身份，包括通信中使用的语言（英语以外）、通信伙伴的国籍以及网页浏览历史作为输入数据。这一策略旨在为未经授权收集和检查数字通信提供法律掩护，对于数据通过美国网络的非公民来说，这是允许的，但对于公民来说，根据美国宪法第四修正案，这是非法的，该修正案禁止无理搜查和扣押。9在数据饥渴算法的帮助下，公民身份从二元的制度类别被重新定义为一系列行为（Cheney-Lippold 2016）。

While algorithms can make intimately lived truths external and modulatory, shifting “the sense by which we take our bearings in the world” (Arendt 2006, p. 252), they are unlikely to fundamentally transform how major structural formations, such as gender or race, operate in the world, as we discussed in the section titled Actuarialism and Its Discontents. Instead, the power of measurable types may be strongest when deployed to legitimize creative expression and self-experimentation (around sexuality, for instance; see Hawgood 2020) or to reform institutional categorization systems. For instance, the Snowden disclosures revealed that the US government, via the National Security Agency, had sought to infer citizenship from digital traces, including language (other than English) used in communication, nationality of communication partners, and web browsing history as input data. This strategy was to provide legal cover for warrantless collection and inspection of digital communications, something allowable for noncitizens whose data pass through US networks but illegal for citizens by the Fourth Amendment of the US Constitution, which prohibits unreasonable search and seizure. 9 With the help of data-hungry algorithms, citizenship was reframed from a binary, institutional category to a continuum of behavior (Cheney-Lippold 2016).

当算法分类器循环回到我们身边时，它们促使我们质疑我们对自己了解多少以及我们是如何了解的（Amoore 2020、Andrejevic 2020、Brubaker 2020、Hong 2016、Neff & Nafus 2016）。然而，我们将发现某种最终的自我真理的想法可能是错误的：相反，我们观察到的可能是在某种自我追踪尺度上令人眼花缭乱的上下运动，或者是对我们自己的多重解构和重构，它们随时间和平台而变化。10 Harcourt（2015 年，第 253页）将我们日益数字化的生活描述为“镜面玻璃亭”，在这个空间里，我们有意识地构建对我们是谁的描述，“为了他人的目光，当然还有我们自己的目光”。但我们几乎无法控制自我描述的参数：暴露和被暴露的欲望已经升华为技术环境，而那些大概能告诉我们个人真相的指标、计算器和可视化工具并非我们自己创造的。无论多么不准确，每日步数、月经周期、心率、情绪状态、社交网络和消费模式都会反映回我们自己、机构其他方（例如医生、保险公司、福利机构）和世界，成为我们是谁的不可否认的证据，超越主观的自我评估或模拟自我呈现的旧技术（Stark 2018）。由于算法工具，我们现在可能会感到有必要不断地在可衡量的生物或社会指标中寻找和发现自己，我们必须以高度合理化、动态和连续的方式管理这些指标（Schüll 2016）。以这种方式监测和调查我们的睡眠模式、饮食习惯和社会关系正慢慢成为我们的第二天性。有时感觉像是好玩的自我诊断，但实际上根本不是玩——相反，它是一种永久的自我探索状态，由人与机器之间不断的反馈循环驱动（Fourcade & Johns 2020）。

As algorithmic classifiers loop back toward us, they prompt us to question what we know about ourselves and how we know it (Amoore 2020, Andrejevic 2020, Brubaker 2020, Hong 2016, Neff & Nafus 2016). The notion that we will discover some ultimate self-truth may be misplaced, however: What we may observe, instead, are bewildering movements up and down some self-tracking scale, or multiple de- and reconstructions of ourselves, varying across time and across platforms. 10 Harcourt (2015, p. 253) describes our increasingly digitized lives as a “mirrored glass pavilion,” a space where we self-consciously construct a depiction of who we are, “[for] the gaze of others and, of course, our own.” But we have little control over the parameters of our self-depictions: The desire to expose and be exposed has been sublimated into the technical environment, and the metrics, calculators, and visualization tools that presumably tell our personal truth are not of our own making. However inaccurate, daily step counts, menstrual cycles, heart rate, emotional states, social networks, and spending patterns are reflected back to us, to institutional others (e.g., doctors, insurance companies, welfare agencies), and to the world as undeniable evidence of who we are over and above subjective self-assessment or the old techniques of analog self-presentation (Stark 2018). Thanks to algorithmic tools, we may now feel compelled to incessantly search for and discover ourselves in measurable biological or social indicators that we must manage in a hyper-rationalized, dynamic, and continuous fashion (Schüll 2016). Monitoring and investigating our sleep patterns, eating habits, and social relations this way is slowly becoming second nature. What may sometimes feel like playful self-diagnosis is really no play at all, however—rather, it is a permanently self-probing condition, powered by incessant feedback loops between human and machine (Fourcade & Johns 2020).

编码精英们迫使我们将主观性交给系统，他们声称这些系统比我们自己更了解我们。但算法只不过是我们自身的部分表征，是被分割又重新组合起来的版本。可以预见，有些版本比其他版本更好。当算法的评估出现令人不安的错误（而不是惊人的准确）时，这个过程可能会特别令人难以忍受（Broussard 2018）。正如我们所见，错误识别的问题（一旦发生）并不是随机分布在人群中的。面部识别系统一再无法识别肤色较深的面孔，并且会不成比例地误认为黑人女性（Buolamwini & Gebru 2018）。搜索引擎结果返回带有偏见的表征，对女性和少数群体成员产生不利影响（Cottom 2017、Noble 2018、Sweeney 2013）。历史上被主导的群体不成比例地成为一种新型象征性暴力的受害者，这种暴力在人机交界处运作。对他们来说，镜面玻璃展馆更像是一个玻璃牢笼——充满了无知、漠视和错误分类，坚称“关于种族身体和个人身份（或多个身份）的真相，无论[个人]如何宣称”（布朗，2015，第110页）。更根本的是，这种机械化加剧了种族化地位等级及其伴随的不平等所造成的对主体性的否定。

The coding elite nudge us to surrender our subjectivity to systems that, they profess, know us better than we know ourselves. But algorithms are nothing but partial representations, sliced-up-and-put-back-together versions of ourselves. Some versions, predictably, are better than others. When algorithms are disturbingly wrong in their assessments (rather than spookily accurate), the process can be especially oppressive (Broussard 2018). And as we have seen, problems of misidentification, when they occur, are not randomly distributed across the population. Facial recognition systems repeatedly fail to recognize faces with dark skin tones and disproportionately misgender Black women (Buolamwini & Gebru 2018). Search engine results return prejudiced representations, adversely affecting women and members of minority groups (Cottom 2017, Noble 2018, Sweeney 2013). Historically dominated groups are disproportionately on the receiving end of a new form of symbolic violence that operates at the interface between humans and machines. For them, the mirrored glass pavilion is more like a glass cage—full of ignorance, disregard, and misclassification, insisting on a “truth about the racial body and one's identity (or identities) despite [one's] claims” (Browne 2015, p. 110). More fundamentally, this mechanization exacerbates the denial of subjectivity already effected by a racialized status hierarchy and its attendant inequalities.

算法界面的道德经济学

用于调解在线互动的庞大数字基础设施大多旨在通过广告创收，并需要人类的眼球和点击量来维持运营。数字公司精心设计社交功能，以实现经济效益最大化（Bucher，2018）。11公司痴迷地追踪用户在特定网站上停留的时间，美其名曰“参与度”，并依靠这些时间生成个人数据，从而最大化广告曝光率。网站访问者需要对进入数字管道的数据进行预处理。标签（例如按钮、表情符号、标签、主题标签、身份验证和其他形式的用户主导操作）有助于对社交世界的混乱进行分类，使其完全可被机器读取（Fourcade & Healy，2017）。但它们也创造了新的可供性，赋予其生命力，推动数字环境中原生的社交动态。12

Much of the vast digital infrastructure mediating online interactions is oriented to generating revenue through advertising and requires human eyeballs and click-throughs to sustain its operations. Digital firms meticulously program sociality so as to yield maximum economic benefit (Bucher 2018). 11 Firms obsessively track time spent on a given site by users, euphemized as “engagement,” which they depend upon to generate personal data and maximize advertising exposure. Site visitors are put to work preprocessing the data entering the digital pipeline. Tags, such as buttons, emojis, labels, hashtags, authentication and other forms of user-directed actions, help categorize the messiness of the social world so that it is rendered machine-readable all the way down (Fourcade & Healy 2017). But they also create new affordances that take a life of their own, fueling social dynamics that are native to the digital environment. 12

像 Facebook 这样的平台所促进的持久性会随着时间的推移延长原本可能逐渐减少的关系，而算法的联想特性与平台的暗示力相结合，使得原本不会存在的关系得以出现。在平台上与人联系的策略性提示、以通知形式发送的被动更新以及利用社会认可和赞同的令人上瘾的设计会滋生社交焦虑、强迫性习惯和竞争倾向（Bishop 2018、Fourcade 和 Johns 2020）。不参与可能会保证某种自由，但也可能意味着社会孤立。大量参与可能会带来名利（Stuart 2020），但也可能带来极度的过度曝光（Cottom 2017）。平台通常发现利用病毒式内容和其他形式的新兴社交性是有利可图的 [也就是说，除非他们将其解释为玩弄算法，在这种情况下必须控制或消除算法（Ziewitz 2019）]。

The persistence facilitated by platforms like Facebook extends relationships over time that might otherwise have dwindled, and the associative properties of algorithms, combined with the platforms’ suggestive power, enables relationships to emerge that would never have existed otherwise. Strategic prompts to connect with people on the platform, passive updates sent as notifications, and addictive designs capitalizing on social recognition and approval foster social anxiety, compulsive habits, and competitive dispositions (Bishop 2018, Fourcade & Johns 2020). Not participating may guarantee a certain kind freedom, but it may also mean social isolation. Participating a lot may lead to fame and fortune (Stuart 2020) but also excruciating overexposure (Cottom 2017). Platforms generally find it profitable to exploit viral content and other forms of emergent sociality [that is, unless they interpret it as gaming the algorithm, in which case it must be controlled or eliminated (Ziewitz 2019)].

通过这些心理和经济手段，Twitter、Facebook、YouTube、Instagram、Reddit 以及其他一些由更少公司运营的数字平台13已经将自己打造成了事实上的全球公共领域，几乎垄断了注意力的社会分配。由于现在大多数人从社交媒体获取信息，任何寻求曝光或追求激进目标的人都必须掌握这一新格局（Tufekci，2017）。公共辩论、知识传播、平权追求和报道都与社交媒体中介及其秘密算法密切相关。但是，人们本应自行解析的海量信息“往往会引发偏执的、投机性的公共知识和参与形式”（Hong，2020，第 8 页）。老牌行为主体已经被技术娴熟或资金雄厚的激进新贵、协调一致的网络暴民和点击诱饵制作者所取代。集体动员和反动员的精神很容易在围绕数字化生产手段的不平等斗争中被淹没（Schradie 2019）。取而代之的是阴谋、信仰和流言蜚语的古老恶魔，它们从坟墓中爬了出来，被贪婪的算法咒语召唤到地面。

Through these psychological and economic techniques, Twitter, Facebook, YouTube, Instagram, Reddit, and a handful of other digital platforms run by even fewer companies 13 have built themselves into a de facto global public sphere with near-monopoly power over the social distribution of attention. With the majority of people now receiving their information from social media, anyone seeking exposure or pursuing activist goals must master this new landscape (Tufekci 2017). Public debate, knowledge circulation, affirmative pursuits, and reportage have all become intimately dependent upon social media intermediaries and their secretive algorithms. But the sheer abundance of information, which people are supposed to parse through on their own, “often provoke[s] paranoid and otherwise speculative forms of public knowledge and participation” (Hong 2020, p. 8). Established actors have been displaced by skilled or well-funded activist upstarts, coordinated online mobs, and clickbait producers. The spirits of collective mobilization and counter-mobilization are easily overwhelmed in the unequal struggle over the means of digital production (Schradie 2019). It is instead the old demons of conspiracy, belief, and gossip that have ascended from their graves, called to the surface by rapacious algorithmic spells.

从算法社会到算法社会

编码精英的最终目标，即他们的专业项目的最终目标，就像他们构建的算法一样，仍然不透明。这可能仅仅反映出缺乏共识；他们的成员在他们所信奉的未来梦想中存在分歧，有时分歧很大。许多计算机科学家持有的最雄心勃勃的愿景是，算法社会只是一个新社会物种出现的前奏，一种可以复制或超越人类智力并可能摆脱人类控制的通用人工智能（Bostrom 2014、Harari 2017、Russell 2019、Tegmark 2017）。摩尔定律规定计算机能力呈指数级增长。如果我们接受衡量智力和进一步发展智力的能力植根于处理能力的前提，那么这条定律就标志着一条清晰的轨迹。

The endgame of the coding elite, the ultimate goal of their professional project, like the algorithms they build, remains opaque. This may simply reflect a lack of consensus; their members diverge from one another, sometimes considerably, in the futuristic dreams they espouse. The most ambitious vision, held by many computer scientists, is that the algorithmic society is simply a prelude to the advent of a new social species, a general AI that will replicate or exceed the intelligence of humans and perhaps escape their control (Bostrom 2014, Harari 2017, Russell 2019, Tegmark 2017). Moore's law specifies that computer power tends to grow exponentially. If we accept the premise that the measure of intelligence and the capacity to develop it further are rooted in processing power, then this law marks a clear trajectory.

然而，人工智能在社会中的发展轨迹不仅仅是人类是否会受益的问题，而是谁会受益的问题。一种新的学习分支将知者与被知者对立起来（Zuboff 2019）；那些让人工智能发挥作用的人面对着那些让人工智能为自己工作的人。与那些被监视、被歪曲和被疏远的人不同，数据资本家可能能够纠正、控制或改进他们的个人数据表述；彻底摆脱监视制度；或者以新的方式从人工智能中获益。最近在开发神经植入物、智能假肢和数据密集型基因工程方面的讨论和具体投资重新唤起了旧的机器人幻想，释放了哈拉维（1990）等人思考的可能性。如果这样的世界成为现实，那么编码精英的成员将处于最佳位置，不仅可以通过宣称对新类型数据输出（例如神经信息）的所有权来增加他们的物质权力，而且还可以真正部署新技术来增强他们自己的思想和身体（Harari 2017）。

AI's trajectory in society, however, is not simply a question of whether humanity will benefit or not but, rather, who will benefit. A new division of learning opposes the knowers against the known (Zuboff 2019); those who make AI work face those who make AI work for themselves. Unlike the mass of those surveilled, those misrepresented and alienated, the data capitalists may be able to correct, control, or improve their personal data representation; to buy themselves entirely out of surveillance regimes; or to benefit from AI in new ways. Recent discussions and concrete investments in developing neural implants, smart prostheses, and data-intensive genetic engineering have revived old cyborg fantasies, unleashing possibilities pondered by Haraway (1990) and others. If such a world came to pass, the members of the coding elite would be best positioned not only to increase their material power by claiming ownership over new kinds of data outputs (e.g., neuro-informational), but also to literally deploy new technologies to augment their own minds and bodies (Harari 2017).

目前，业界主流观点承诺人工智能将更加温和、更容易被接受、偏见更少，符合最佳实践并符合伦理道德（Crawford & Calo 2016）。但是，尽管人们热议公平和价值观一致（Gabriel 2020），但既定的技术轨迹依然稳固：风险投资机构和初创公司继续构建一个无处不在的计算世界，从人体和普通物体到城市基础设施和其他大型工程，计算无处不在。算法将继续利用将人转化为无形数据流这一过程。随着这个平行的数据宇宙成为第二天性，有血有肉的人类可能会学会将彼此（以及自己）理解为极具可塑性的算法结构，他们必须谨慎、持续地迎合这些结构。

For now, dominant industry talk promises a gentler, more acceptable, less biased kind of AI, compliant with best practices and ethically infused (Crawford & Calo 2016). But for all the great chatter about equity and value alignment (Gabriel 2020), the established technological trajectory has remained secure: Venture capital offices and start-up firms continue to roll out a world of ubiquitous computing, located in everything from human bodies and mundane objects to city infrastructures and other large works of engineering. Algorithms will continue to capitalize on the transformation of persons into disembodied data streams. And as this parallel dataverse becomes second nature, actual flesh and blood people may learn to apprehend each other (and themselves) as eminently malleable algorithmic constructs that they must carefully, continuously, cater to.

多年来，许多人宣称摩尔定律即将终结。14那些最有能力实现这一目标的技术专家认为，人类距离开发出像人类一样的通用人工智能还有很长的路要走，距离超级智能则更远。15不加批判地接受编码精英最狂热的支持者的狂热梦想，以“神学而不是科学或文化”的方式对待计算，将是一个错误（Bogost 2015）。在这方面，社会学提供了一个有用的现实检验。观察数字技术实际应用的民族志学家出色地处理了算法平淡无奇的日常现实。他们记录了对算法系统的巨大抵制、频繁的错误和故障，以及在不同社会和社会内部含义和效果的差异（Brayne 2020、Christin 2020、Rafalow 2020）。我们既可以拒绝对机器智能的神奇想象，又可以承认科技产业在改变我们生活的世界方面拥有巨大的经济、政治和文化力量。抛开未来主义和炒作，现有的人工智能其实相当平凡。16它由编程精英设计，由网络精英维持，由（主要）大型数字公司提取的个人数据驱动，经常为实现利润最大化而进行优化，并得到一套法律机构的支持，这些机构授权（在撰写本文时）数据连续流入企业和国家服务器。与之前的控制创新一样，人工智能可以监视、分类、解析、组装和自动化。并且与之前的社会监视和纪律形式一样，它对贫困人口和少数族裔的影响不同，而且更具偏见。它远非纯粹的机械，而是深刻的、不可避免的人性。

For years now, many have proclaimed that the end of Moore's law is imminent. 14 Humanity is still a considerable distance from developing human-like general AI and is yet further from superintelligence, according to those technical experts best positioned to bring about such a scenario. 15 It would be a mistake to uncritically embrace the fever dreams of the coding elite's most fervent boosters, to treat computing “theologically rather than scientifically or culturally” (Bogost 2015). In that respect, sociology offers a useful reality check. Ethnographers who observe digital technology in action have brilliantly tackled the unglamorous everyday realities of algorithms. They have documented considerable resistance to algorithmic systems, frequent errors and breakdowns, and variations in meaning and effect, both across and within societies (Brayne 2020, Christin 2020, Rafalow 2020). We can both reject magical thinking about machine intelligence and acknowledge the enormous economic, political, and cultural power of the tech industry to transform the world we live in. Beyond futurism and hype, existing AI is actually quite mundane. 16 It is designed by the coding elite, sustained by the cybertariat, fueled by personal data extracted by (mainly) large digital firms, frequently optimized for profit maximization, and supported by a contingent set of legal institutions that authorize (at the time of this writing) continuous data flows into corporate as well as state servers. Like prior control innovations, AI surveils, sorts, parses, assembles, and automates. And like prior forms of social surveillance and discipline, it weighs differently and more prejudicially on poor and minority populations. Far from being purely mechanistic, it is deeply, inescapably human.
